# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The **Indian Rebellion of 1857** was a major uprising in India in 1857–58 against the rule of the British East India Company, which functioned as a sovereign power, including military forces, on behalf of the British Crown.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The rebellion began on 10 May 1857 as a mutiny of sepoys of the company's garrison in Meerut, a town 40 miles (64 km) northeast of Delhi.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] It then erupted into other mutinies and civilian rebellions, chiefly in the upper Gangetic plain and central India, though incidents of revolt also occurred farther north and east.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The rebellion posed a military threat to British power in that region, and was contained only with the rebels' defeat in Gwalior on 20 June 1858.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] On 1 November 1858, the British granted amnesty to all rebels not involved in murder, though they did not declare the hostilities to have formally ended until 8 July 1859.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The name of the revolt is contested, and it is variously described as the **Sepoy Mutiny**, the **Indian Mutiny**, the **Great Rebellion**, the **Revolt of 1857**, the **Indian Insurrection**, and the **First War of Independence**.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Indian rebellion was fed by resentments born of diverse perceptions, including invasive British-style social reforms, harsh land taxes, summary treatment of some rich landowners and princes, and scepticism about British claims that their rule offered material improvement to the Indian economy.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Many Indians rose against the British; however, many also fought for the British, and the majority remained seemingly compliant to British rule.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] After the outbreak of the mutiny in Meerut, the rebels quickly reached Delhi, whose 81-year-old Mughal ruler, Bahadur Shah Zafar, was declared the Emperor of Hindustan.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Soon, the rebels had captured large tracts of the North-Western Provinces and Awadh (Oudh).
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The East India Company's response came rapidly as well.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] With help from reinforcements, Kanpur was retaken by mid-July 1857, and Delhi by the end of September.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] However, it then took the remainder of 1857 and the better part of 1858 for the rebellion to be suppressed in Jhansi, Lucknow, and especially the Awadh countryside.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Other regions of Company-controlled India—Bengal province, the Bombay Presidency, and the Madras Presidency—remained largely calm.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In the Punjab, the Sikh princes crucially helped the British by providing both soldiers and support.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The large princely states, Hyderabad, Mysore, Travancore, and Kashmir, as well as the smaller ones of Rajputana, did not join the rebellion, serving the British, in Governor-General Lord Canning's words, as "breakwaters in a storm".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In some regions, most notably in Awadh, the rebellion took on the attributes of a patriotic revolt against British oppression.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] However, the rebel leaders proclaimed no articles of faith that presaged a new political system.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Even so, the rebellion proved to be an important watershed in Indian and British Empire history.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] It led to the dissolution of the East India Company and forced the British to reorganize the army, the financial system, and the administration in India through passage of the Government of India Act 1858.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] India was thereafter administered directly by the British government in the new British Raj.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] On 1 November 1858, Queen Victoria issued a proclamation to Indians, which, while lacking the authority of a constitutional provision, promised rights similar to those of other British subjects.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In the following decades, when admission to these rights was not always forthcoming, Indians were to pointedly refer to the Queen's proclamation in growing avowals of a new nationalism.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Although the British East India Company had established a presence in India as far back as 1612, and earlier administered the factory areas established for trading purposes, its victory in the Battle of Plassey in 1757 marked the beginning of its firm foothold in eastern India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The victory was consolidated in 1764 at the Battle of Buxar, when the East India Company army defeated Mughal Emperor Shah Alam II.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] After his defeat, the emperor granted the company the right to the "collection of Revenue" in the provinces of Bengal (modern day Bengal, Bihar, and Odisha), known as "Diwani" to the company.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Company soon expanded its territories around its bases in Bombay and Madras; later, the Anglo-Mysore Wars (1766–1799) and the Anglo-Maratha Wars (1772–1818) led to control of even more of India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In 1806, the Vellore Mutiny was sparked by new uniform regulations that created resentment amongst both Hindu and Muslim sepoys.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] After the turn of the 19th century, Governor-General Wellesley began what became two decades of accelerated expansion of Company territories.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] This was achieved either by subsidiary alliances between the company and local rulers or by direct military annexation.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The subsidiary alliances created the princely states of the Hindu maharajas and the Muslim nawabs.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Punjab, North-West Frontier Province, and Kashmir were annexed after the Second Anglo-Sikh War in 1849; however, Kashmir was immediately sold under the 1846 Treaty of Amritsar to the Dogra Dynasty of Jammu and thereby became a princely state.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The border dispute between Nepal and British India, which sharpened after 1801, had caused the Anglo-Nepalese War of 1814–1816 and brought the defeated Gurkhas under British influence.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In 1854, Berar was annexed, and the state of Oudh was added two years later.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] For practical purposes, the company was the government of much of India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Indian Rebellion of 1857 occurred as the result of an accumulation of factors over time, rather than any single event.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The *sepoys* were Indian soldiers who were recruited into the company's army.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Just before the rebellion, there were over 300,000 sepoys in the army, compared to about 50,000 British.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The East India Company's forces were divided into three presidency armies: Bombay, Madras, and Bengal.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Bengal Army recruited higher castes, such as Brahmins, Rajputs and Bhumihar, mostly from the Awadh and Bihar regions, and even restricted the enlistment of lower castes in 1855.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In contrast, the Madras Army and Bombay Army were "more localized, caste-neutral armies" that "did not prefer high-caste men".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The domination of higher castes in the Bengal Army has been blamed in part for initial mutinies that led to the rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In 1772, when Warren Hastings was appointed Fort William's first Governor-General, one of his first undertakings was the rapid expansion of the company's army.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Since the sepoys from Bengal – many of whom had fought against the Company in the Battles of Plassey and Buxar – were now suspect in British eyes, Hastings recruited farther west from the high-caste rural Rajputs and Bhumihar of Awadh and Bihar, a practice that continued for the next 75 years.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] However, in order to forestall any social friction, the company also took action to adapt its military practices to the requirements of their religious rituals.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Consequently, these soldiers dined in separate facilities; in addition, overseas service, considered polluting to their caste, was not required of them, and the army soon came officially to recognise Hindu festivals.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] After the annexation of Oudh (Awadh) by the East India Company in 1856, many sepoys were disquieted both from losing their perquisites, as landed gentry, in the Oudh courts, and from the anticipation of any increased land-revenue payments that the annexation might bring about.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Other historians have stressed that by 1857, some Indian soldiers, interpreting the presence of missionaries as a sign of official intent, were convinced that the company was masterminding mass conversions of Hindus and Muslims to Christianity.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Changes in the terms of their professional service may have created resentment.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] As the extent of the East India Company's jurisdiction expanded with victories in wars or annexation, the soldiers were now expected not only to serve in less familiar regions, such as in Burma, but also to make do without the "foreign service" remuneration that had previously been their due.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] A major cause of resentment that arose ten months prior to the outbreak of the rebellion was the General Service Enlistment Act of 25 July 1856.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] As noted above, men of the Bengal Army had been exempted from overseas service.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Specifically, they were enlisted only for service in territories to which they could march.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Governor-General Lord Dalhousie saw this as an anomaly, since all sepoys of the Madras and Bombay Armies and the six "General Service" battalions of the Bengal Army had accepted an obligation to serve overseas if required.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] As a result, the burden of providing contingents for active service in Burma, readily accessible only by sea, and China had fallen disproportionately on the two smaller Presidency Armies.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] As signed into effect by Lord Canning, Dalhousie's successor as Governor-General, the act required only new recruits to the Bengal Army to accept a commitment for general service.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] However, serving high-caste sepoys were fearful that it would be eventually extended to them, as well as preventing sons following fathers into an army with a strong tradition of family service.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] There were also grievances over the issue of promotions, based on seniority.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] This, as well as the increasing number of British officers in the battalions, made promotion slow, and many Indian officers did not reach commissioned rank until they were too old to be effective.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The immediate flashpoint for the 1857 uprising is often associated with the introduction of the Pattern 1853 Enfield rifle-musket into the Bengal Army.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] These rifles used paper cartridges that were pre-greased to allow smooth loading.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] To load the rifle, a soldier tore open the cartridge, traditionally with his teeth, before pouring the powder down the barrel and ramming home the bullet and wadding.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In early 1857, rumours began circulating among sepoys that the grease used on these cartridges was derived from cow tallow, offensive to Hindus, and pig lard, offensive to Muslims.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] These rumours caused deep alarm because biting the cartridge could be perceived as a violation of religious practice.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Modern historians emphasize that it was the belief in these rumours, rather than the confirmed presence of animal fat, that inflamed tensions.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Kim Wagner argues that there is little direct evidence that large numbers of greased cartridges were actually issued to Indian troops before the revolt.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Instead, the affair reflects a broader climate of distrust in which fears of religious pollution merged with anxieties about British intentions toward Indian society and religion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] British officials became aware of the rumours through reports of disputes between sepoys and labourers at military depots such as Dum Dum and Barrackpore.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In response, the Company ordered that future cartridges be supplied without grease and allowed sepoys to apply their own lubricant.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] This measure failed to calm fears and, in some cases, reinforced the suspicion that the authorities were concealing the truth.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The "greased cartridge affair" became a powerful symbol of British cultural insensitivity and fed into broader grievances over pay, conditions of service, and the perception that the Company was seeking to erode traditional religious and social structures.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Historians now view the controversy less as a single cause and more as a catalyst that helped turn widespread discontent into open rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Civilian participation in the rebellion was diverse and regionally varied, involving three main groups: the traditional feudal nobility, rural landlords known as *taluqdars*, and the peasantry.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The feudal nobility included princes and chieftains whose power had been curtailed by British expansionist policies such as the Doctrine of Lapse, which denied recognition to adopted heirs of deceased rulers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Many nobles, such as Nana Sahib and Rani of Jhansi, had initially been willing to accept British supremacy but rebelled when their legal and hereditary claims were rejected.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] For instance, the Rani of Jhansi resisted British authority after her adopted son was denied recognition as her late husband's successor.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In regions like Indore and Sagar, where princely privileges were not directly threatened, many rulers remained loyal to the British even when local sepoys revolted.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The taluqdars, particularly in Oudh and Bihar, played a decisive role in the uprising.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] British land-revenue policies and annexations had stripped many taluqdars of their traditional estates, transferring large portions of land to peasant farmers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] During the rebellion, Rajput taluqdars provided much of the leadership in Oudh, while in Bihar, figures like Kunwar Singh emerged as prominent leaders.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] As the rebellion spread, taluqdars reasserted control over their lost territories, often with the support of peasants bound to them by kinship and feudal loyalty.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] British officials were surprised at the lack of resistance from these peasant groups, many of whom actively joined the revolt.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Heavy land-revenue assessments imposed by the Company also contributed to widespread rural discontent.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Many landowners were forced into debt or bankruptcy, creating deep resentment toward both the British and moneylenders who profited from these policies.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Moneylenders became symbolic targets of popular anger, alongside Company officials.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Despite the widespread participation of civilians, the rebellion was geographically uneven.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Even within rebellious regions of north-central India, some districts remained calm.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] For example, the prosperous Muzaffarnagar district, which benefited from a Company-sponsored irrigation project, stayed largely loyal to British authority despite its proximity to Meerut, where the uprising began.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Reformist policies introduced by the Company were also viewed with suspicion by many Indians.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Utilitarian and evangelical-inspired reforms, such as the abolition of sati and the legalisation of widow remarriage, were interpreted by some as attempts to undermine traditional Indian religions and promote Christian conversion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Historian Christopher Bayly has described the uprising as, in part, a "clash of knowledges," in which traditional religious and social authorities, including pandits, maulvis, and astrologers, perceived British colonial educational and medical policies as a direct threat to established hierarchies.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Testimonies collected after the rebellion, such as those recorded in the 1858 Parliamentary Blue Books, reveal that British-run schools were especially controversial.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Many parents feared that the exclusion of religious instruction and the introduction of secular subjects like mathematics and Western science, as well as the education of girls, undermined traditional moral and spiritual values.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The colonial justice system was also widely perceived as biased.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Official reports, such as the *East India (Torture) 1855–1857* Blue Books laid before the House of Commons, documented that Company officers accused of brutality against Indians were often shielded by extended appeals processes and rarely faced meaningful punishment.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Finally, the economic policies of the East India Company, including high taxation and export-oriented trade practices, were deeply resented by many communities.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] These policies disrupted traditional industries and contributed to widespread hardship, further fueling rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Each of the three "Presidencies" into which the East India Company divided India for administrative purposes maintained its own army.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Of these, the Army of the Bengal Presidency was the largest.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Unlike the other two presidency armies, it recruited heavily from among high-status Hindus and comparatively wealthy Muslims.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Muslims formed a larger percentage of the 18 irregular cavalry units.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Hindus were mainly found in the 84 regular infantry and cavalry regiments.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] About 75% of the cavalry was composed of Indian Muslims.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Roughly 80% of the infantry consisted of Hindus.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] During the early years of Company rule, authorities tolerated and even encouraged the social and religious practices of their recruits.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Bengal Army's regular infantry was drawn almost exclusively from the landowning Rajput and Brahmin communities of Bihar and Oudh, collectively known as Purbiyas.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] From the 1840s onward, administrative reforms introduced in Calcutta began to erode many of these long-standing privileges.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Having grown accustomed to high social and ritual standing, the sepoys became increasingly sensitive to policies or actions they perceived as threatening their religious purity or social status.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The sepoys also grew dissatisfied with other aspects of army life.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Pay was relatively low, and following the annexations of Oudh and the Punjab, soldiers no longer received extra allowances (*batta* or *bhatta*) for service there, as these regions were no longer classified as "foreign missions".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Relations between British junior officers and sepoys deteriorated as many officers increasingly treated their men as racial inferiors.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In 1856, the Company introduced a new Enlistment Act making all units in the Bengal Army theoretically liable for overseas service.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Although intended only for new recruits, many serving sepoys feared it might be applied retroactively.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Hindu soldiers in particular were alarmed, as sea voyages under cramped shipboard conditions made it impossible to follow essential religious practices, raising fears of ritual defilement and social ostracism.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Several months of increasing tensions coupled with various incidents preceded the actual rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] On 26 February 1857 the 19th Bengal Native Infantry (BNI) regiment became concerned that new cartridges they had been issued were wrapped in paper greased with cow and pig fat, which had to be opened by mouth thus affecting their religious sensibilities.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Their Colonel confronted them supported by artillery and cavalry on the parade ground, but after some negotiation withdrew the artillery, and cancelled the next morning's parade.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] On 29 March 1857 at the Barrackpore parade ground, near Calcutta, 29-year-old Mangal Pandey of the 34th BNI, angered by the recent actions of the East India Company, declared that he would rebel against his commanders.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Informed about Pandey's behaviour Sergeant-Major James Hewson went to investigate, only to have Pandey shoot at him.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Henry Baugh came out to investigate the unrest, Pandey opened fire but hit Baugh's horse instead.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] General John Hearsey came out to the parade ground to investigate, and claimed later that Mangal Pandey was in some kind of "religious frenzy".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] He ordered the Indian commander of the quarter guard, Jemadar Ishwari Prasad, to arrest Mangal Pandey, but the Jemadar refused.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The quarter guard and other sepoys present, with the single exception of a soldier called Shaikh Paltu, drew back from restraining or arresting Mangal Pandey.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Shaikh Paltu restrained Pandey from continuing his attack.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] After failing to incite his comrades into an open and active rebellion, Mangal Pandey tried to take his own life, by placing his musket to his chest and pulling the trigger with his toe.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] He was court-martialled on 6 April and hanged two days later.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Jemadar Ishwari Prasad was sentenced to death and hanged on 21 April.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The regiment was disbanded and stripped of its uniforms because it was felt that it harboured ill-feelings towards its superiors, particularly after this incident.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Shaikh Paltu was promoted to the rank of havildar in the Bengal Army but was murdered shortly before the 34th BNI dispersed.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Sepoys in other regiments thought these punishments were harsh.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The demonstration of disgrace during the formal disbanding helped foment the rebellion in view of some historians.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Disgruntled ex-sepoys returned home to Awadh with a desire for revenge.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] During April, there were unrest and fires at Agra, Allahabad and Ambala.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] At Ambala in particular, which was a large military cantonment where several units had been collected for their annual musketry practice, it was clear to General Anson, Commander-in-Chief of the Bengal Army, that some sort of rebellion over the cartridges was imminent.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Despite the objections of the civilian Governor-General's staff, he agreed to postpone the musketry practice and allow a new drill by which the soldiers tore the cartridges with their fingers rather than their teeth.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] He issued no general orders making this standard practice throughout the Bengal Army and, rather than remain at Ambala to defuse or overawe potential trouble, he then proceeded to Simla, the cool hill station where many high officials spent the summer.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Although there was no open revolt at Ambala, there was widespread arson during late April.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Barrack buildings (especially those belonging to soldiers who had used the Enfield cartridges) and British officers' bungalows were set on fire.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] At Meerut, a large military cantonment, 2,357 Indian sepoys and 2,038 British soldiers were stationed along with 12 British-manned guns.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The station held one of the largest concentrations of British troops in India and this was later cited as evidence that the original rising was a spontaneous outbreak rather than a pre-planned plot.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Although the state of unrest within the Bengal Army was well known, on 24 April Lieutenant Colonel George Carmichael-Smyth, the unsympathetic commanding officer of the 3rd Bengal Light Cavalry, which was composed mainly of Indian Muslims, ordered 90 of his men to parade and perform firing drills.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] All except five of the men on parade refused to accept their cartridges.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] On 9 May, the remaining 85 men were court martialled, and most were sentenced to 10 years' imprisonment with hard labour.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Eleven comparatively young soldiers were given five years' imprisonment.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The entire garrison was paraded and watched as the condemned men were stripped of their uniforms and placed in shackles.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] As they were marched off to jail, the condemned soldiers berated their comrades for failing to support them.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Some Indian soldiers warned off-duty junior British officers that plans were afoot to release the imprisoned soldiers by force, but the senior officers to whom this was reported took no action.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] There was also unrest in the city of Meerut itself, with angry protests in the bazaar and some buildings being set on fire.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In the evening, most British officers were preparing to attend church, while many of the British soldiers were off duty and had gone into canteens or into the bazaar in Meerut.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Indian troops, led by the 3rd Cavalry, broke into revolt.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] British junior officers who attempted to quell the first outbreaks were killed by the rebels.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] British officers' and civilians' quarters were attacked, and four civilian men, eight women and eight children were killed.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Crowds in the bazaar attacked off-duty soldiers there.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] About 50 Indian civilians, some of them officers' servants who tried to defend or conceal their employers, were killed by the sepoys.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] While the action of the sepoys in freeing their 85 imprisoned comrades appears to have been spontaneous, some civilian rioting in the city was reportedly encouraged by Kotwal (chief police officer) Dhan Singh Gurjar.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Some sepoys (especially from the 11th Bengal Native Infantry) escorted trusted British officers and women and children to safety before joining the revolt.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Some officers and their families escaped to Rampur, where they found refuge with the Nawab.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The British historian Philip Mason notes that it was inevitable that most of the sepoys and sowars from Meerut should have made for Delhi on the night of 10 May.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] It was a strong walled city located only forty miles away, it was the ancient capital and present seat of the nominal Mughal Emperor, and there were no British troops in garrison there, in contrast to Meerut.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Early on 11 May, the first parties of the 3rd Cavalry reached Delhi.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] From beneath the windows of Emperor Bahadur Shah II's apartments in the palace, they called on the Emperor to acknowledge and lead them.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] He did nothing at this point, apparently treating the sepoys as ordinary petitioners, but others in the palace were quick to join the revolt.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] British officials and dependents, Indian Christians and shop keepers within the city were killed, some by sepoys and others by crowds of rioters.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] There were three battalion-sized regiments of Bengal Native Infantry stationed in or near the city.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Some detachments quickly joined the rebellion, while others held back but also refused to obey orders to take action against the rebels.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In the afternoon, a violent explosion in the city was heard for several miles.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Fearing that the arsenal, which contained large stocks of arms and ammunition, would fall intact into rebel hands, the nine British Ordnance officers there had opened fire on the sepoys, including the men of their own guard.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] When resistance appeared hopeless, they blew up the arsenal.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Six of the nine officers survived, but the blast killed many in the streets and nearby houses and other buildings.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The news of these events finally tipped the sepoys stationed around Delhi into open rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The sepoys were later able to salvage at least some arms from the arsenal.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] A magazine 3 km (1.9 mi) outside Delhi, containing up to 3,000 barrels of gunpowder, was captured without resistance.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Many fugitive British officers and civilians had congregated at the Flagstaff Tower on the ridge north of Delhi, where telegraph operators were sending news of the events to other British stations.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] When it became clear that the help expected from Meerut was not coming, they made their way in carriages to Karnal.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Those who became separated from the main body or who could not reach the Flagstaff Tower also set out for Karnal on foot.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Some were helped by villagers on the way; others were killed.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The next day, Bahadur Shah held his first formal court in years.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The emperor was alarmed by the turn events had taken, but eventually accepted the sepoys' allegiance and agreed to give his countenance to the rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] On 16 May, up to 50 British who had been held prisoner in the palace or had been discovered hiding in the city were killed by some of the emperor's servants in a courtyard outside the palace.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The news of the events at Meerut and Delhi spread rapidly, provoking uprisings among sepoys and disturbances in many districts.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] In many cases, it was the behaviour of British military and civilian authorities themselves which precipitated disorder.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Learning of the fall of Delhi, many Company administrators hastened to remove themselves, their families and servants to places of safety.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] At Agra, 160 miles (260 km) from Delhi, no fewer than 6,000 assorted non-combatants converged on the Fort.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The military authorities also reacted in disjointed manner.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Some officers trusted their sepoys, but others tried to disarm them to forestall potential uprisings.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] At Benares and Allahabad, the disarmings were bungled, also leading to local revolts.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] There were 311,000 native soldiers in India altogether, 40,160 British soldiers (including units of the British Army) and 5,362 officers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Fifty-four of the Bengal Army's 74 regular Native Infantry Regiments mutinied, but some were immediately destroyed or broke up, with their sepoys drifting away to their homes.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] A number of the remaining 20 regiments were disarmed or disbanded to prevent or forestall mutiny.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Only twelve of the original Bengal Native Infantry regiments survived to pass into the new Indian Army.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] All ten of the Bengal Light Cavalry regiments mutinied.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Bengal Army also contained 29 irregular cavalry and 42 irregular infantry regiments.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Of these, a substantial contingent from the recently annexed state of Awadh mutinied *en masse*.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Another large contingent from Gwalior also mutinied, even though that state's king (Jayajirao Scindia) supported the British.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The remainder of the irregular units were raised from a wide variety of sources and were less affected by the concerns of mainstream Indian society.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Some irregular units actively supported the company: three Gurkha and five of six Sikh infantry units, and the six infantry and six cavalry units of the recently raised Punjab Irregular Force.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] On 1 April 1858, the number of Indian soldiers in the Bengal army loyal to the company was 80,053.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] However large numbers were hastily raised in the Punjab and North-West Frontier after the outbreak of the Rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Bombay army had three mutinies in its 29 regiments, whilst the Madras Army had none at all, although elements of one of its 52 regiments refused to volunteer for service in Bengal.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Nonetheless, most of southern India remained passive, with only intermittent outbreaks of violence.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Many parts of the region were ruled by the Nizams or the Mysore royalty, and were thus not directly under British rule.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Although most of the mutinous sepoys in Delhi were Hindus, a significant proportion of the insurgents were Muslims.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The proportion of *ghazis* grew to be about a quarter of the local fighting force by the end of the siege and included a regiment of suicide *ghazis* from Gwalior who had vowed never to eat again and to fight until they met certain death at the hands of British troops.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] However, most Muslims did not share the rebels' dislike of the British administration and their ulema could not agree on whether to declare a jihad.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Some Islamic scholars such as Maulana Muhammad Qasim Nanautavi and Maulana Rashid Ahmad Gangohi took up arms against the colonial rule, but many Muslims, among them ulema from both the Sunni and Shia sects, sided with the British.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] Various Ahl-i-Hadith scholars and colleagues of Nanautavi rejected the jihad.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Sikhs and Pathans of the Punjab and North-West Frontier Province supported the British and helped in the recapture of Delhi.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Sikhs in particular feared reinstatement of Mughal rule in northern India because they had been persecuted by the Mughal Empire.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] They also felt disdain towards the *Purbiyas* or 'Easterners' (Biharis and those from the United Provinces of Agra and Oudh) in the Bengal Army.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The Sikhs felt that the bloodiest battles of the First and Second Anglo-Sikh wars (Chillianwala and Ferozeshah), had been won by British troops, while the Hindustani sepoys had refused to meet the Sikhs in battle.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] These feelings were compounded when Hindustani sepoys were assigned a very visible role as garrison troops in Punjab and awarded profit-making civil posts in the Punjab.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p01] The varied groups in the support and opposing of the uprising is seen as a major cause of its failure.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Bahadur Shah II was proclaimed the Emperor of the whole of India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Most contemporary and modern accounts suggest that he was coerced by the sepoys and his courtiers to sign the proclamation against his will.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In spite of the significant loss of power that the Mughal dynasty had suffered in the preceding centuries, their name still carried great prestige across northern India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Civilians, nobility and other dignitaries took an oath of allegiance.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The emperor issued coins in his name, one of the oldest ways of asserting imperial status.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The adhesion of the Mughal emperor, however, turned the Sikhs of the Punjab away from the rebellion, as they did not want to return to Islamic rule, having fought many wars against the Mughal rulers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The province of Bengal was largely quiet throughout the entire period.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British, who had long ceased to take the authority of the Mughal Emperor seriously, were astonished at how the ordinary people responded to Bahadur Shah's call for war.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Initially, the Indian rebels were able to push back Company forces, and captured several important towns in Haryana, Bihar, the Central Provinces and the United Provinces.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] When British troops were reinforced and began to counterattack, the mutineers were especially handicapped by their lack of centralized command and control.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Although the rebels produced some natural leaders such as Bakht Khan, whom the Emperor later nominated as commander-in-chief after his son Mirza Mughal proved ineffectual, for the most part they were forced to look for leadership to rajahs and princes.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Some of these were to prove dedicated leaders, but others were self-interested or inept.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In the countryside around Meerut, a general Gurjar uprising posed the largest threat to the British.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In Parikshitgarh near Meerut, Gurjars declared Rao Kadam Singh (Kuddum Singh) their leader, and expelled Company police.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Kadam Singh Gurjar led a large force, estimates varying from 2,000 to 10,000.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Bulandshahr and Bijnor also came under the control of Gurjars under Walidad Khan and Maho Singh respectively.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Imperial Gazetteer of India states that throughout the Indian Rebellion of 1857, Gurjars and Ranghars proved the "most irreconcilable enemies" of the British in the Bulandshahr area.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Mufti Nizamuddin, a renowned scholar of Lahore, issued a Fatwa against the British forces and called upon the local population to support the forces of Rao Tula Ram.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Casualties were high at the subsequent engagement at Narnaul (Nasibpur).
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After the defeat of Rao Tula Ram on 16 November 1857, Mufti Nizamuddin was arrested, and his brother Mufti Yaqinuddin and brother-in-law Abdur Rahman (alias Nabi Baksh) were arrested in Tijara.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British were slow to strike back at first.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] It took time for troops stationed in Britain to make their way to India by sea, although some regiments moved overland through Persia from the Crimean War, and some regiments already *en route* for China were diverted to India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] It took time to organise the British troops already in India into field forces, but eventually two columns left Meerut and Simla.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] They proceeded slowly towards Delhi and fought, killed, and hanged numerous Indians along the way.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Two months after the first outbreak of rebellion at Meerut, the two forces met near Karnal.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The combined force, including two Gurkha units serving in the Bengal Army under contract from the Kingdom of Nepal, fought the rebels' main army at Badli-ke-Serai and drove them back to Delhi.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The company's army established a base on the Delhi ridge to the north of the city and the Siege of Delhi began.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The siege lasted roughly from 1 July to 21 September.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] However, the encirclement was hardly complete, and for much of the siege the besiegers were outnumbered and it often seemed that it was the Company forces and not Delhi that were under siege, as the rebels could easily receive resources and reinforcements.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On 30 August the rebels offered terms, which were refused.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] An eagerly awaited heavy siege train joined the besieging force, and from 7 September, the siege guns battered breaches in the walls and silenced the rebels' artillery.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] An attempt to storm the city through the breaches and the Kashmiri Gate was launched on 14 September.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The attackers gained a foothold within the city but suffered heavy casualties, including John Nicholson.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Major General Archdale Wilson, the British commander, wished to withdraw, but was persuaded to hold on by his junior officers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After a week of street fighting, the British reached the Red Fort.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Bahadur Shah Zafar had already fled to Humayun's tomb.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The troops of the besieging force proceeded to loot and pillage the city.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] A large number of citizens were killed in retaliation for the British and Indian civilians that had been slaughtered by the rebels.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] During the street fighting, artillery was set up in the city's main mosque.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Neighbourhoods within range were bombarded; the homes of the Muslim nobility that housed innumerable cultural, artistic, literary and monetary riches were destroyed.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British soon arrested Bahadur Shah Zafar, and the next day the British Major William Hodson had his sons Mirza Mughal and Mirza Khizr Sultan and grandson Mirza Abu Bakr shot under his own authority at the Khooni Darwaza (the bloody gate) near Delhi Gate.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On hearing the news, Zafar reacted with shocked silence, while his wife Zinat Mahal was content, as she believed her son was now Zafar's heir.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Shortly after the fall of Delhi, the victorious attackers organised a column that relieved another besieged Company force in Agra, and then pressed on to Cawnpore, which had also recently been retaken.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] This gave the Company forces a continuous, although still tenuous, line of communication from the east to the west of India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In June, sepoys under General Wheeler in Cawnpore (now Kanpur) rebelled and besieged the British entrenchment.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Wheeler was not only a veteran and respected soldier but also married to an Indian woman.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] He had relied on his own prestige and his cordial relations with local landholder and hereditary prime minister Nana Sahib to thwart rebellion, and took comparatively few measures to prepare fortifications and lay in supplies and ammunition.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Advised by his trusted consultant Azimullah Khan, Nana Sahib led the rebels at Kanpur rather than join the Mughals in Delhi.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The besieged endured three weeks of the Siege of Cawnpore with little water or food, suffering continuous casualties among men, women and children.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On 25 June Nana Sahib made an offer of safe passage to Allahabad.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] With barely three days' food rations remaining, the British agreed, provided they could keep their small arms and that the evacuation should take place in daylight on the morning of the 27th (the Nana Sahib wanted the evacuation to take place on the night of the 26th).
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Early in the morning of 27 June, the British party left their entrenchment and made their way to the river where boats provided by the Nana Sahib were waiting to take them to Allahabad.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Several sepoys who had stayed loyal to the company were removed by the mutineers and killed, either because of their loyalty or because "they had become Christian".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] A few injured British officers trailing the column were also apparently hacked to death by angry sepoys.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After the British party had largely arrived at the dock, which was surrounded by sepoys positioned on both banks of the Ganges, with clear lines of fire, firing broke out and the boats were abandoned by their crew, and caught or were set on fire using pieces of red-hot charcoal.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British party tried to push the boats off but all except three remained stuck.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] One boat with over a dozen wounded men initially escaped, but later grounded, was caught by mutineers and pushed back down the river towards the carnage at Cawnpore.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Towards the end, rebel cavalry rode into the water to finish off any survivors.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After the firing ceased the survivors were rounded up and the men shot.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] By the time the massacre was over, most of the male members of the party were dead while the surviving women and children were removed and held hostage to be later killed in the Bibighar massacre.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Only four men eventually escaped alive from Cawnpore on one of the boats: two private soldiers, a lieutenant, and Captain Mowbray Thomson, who wrote a first-hand account of his experiences entitled *The Story of Cawnpore* (London, 1859).
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] During his trial, Tatya Tope denied the existence of any such plan and described the incident in the following terms: the British had already boarded the boats and Tatya Tope raised his right hand to signal their departure.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] That very moment someone from the crowd blew a loud bugle, which created disorder and in the ongoing bewilderment, the boatmen jumped off the boats.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The rebels started shooting indiscriminately.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Nana Sahib, who was staying in Savada Kothi (Bungalow) nearby, was informed about what was happening and immediately came to stop it.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Some British histories allow that it might well have been the result of accident or error; someone accidentally or maliciously fired a shot, the panic-stricken British opened fire, and it became impossible to stop the massacre.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The surviving women and children were taken to Nana Sahib and then confined first to the Savada Kothi and then to the home of the local magistrate's clerk (the Bibighar) where they were joined by refugees from Fatehgarh.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Overall, five men and 206 women and children were confined in the Bibigarh for about two weeks.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In one week 25 were brought out, dead from dysentery and cholera.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Meanwhile, a Company relief force that had advanced from Allahabad defeated the Indians and by 15 July it was clear that Nana Sahib would not be able to hold Cawnpore and a decision was made by Nana Sahib and other leading rebels that the hostages must be killed.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After the sepoys refused to carry out this order, two Muslim butchers, two Hindu peasants and one of Nana's bodyguards went into the Bibigarh.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Armed with knives and hatchets, they murdered the women and children.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After the massacre, the walls were covered in bloody handprints, and the floor littered with parts of human limbs.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The dead and the dying were thrown down a nearby well.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] When the 50-foot (15 m) deep well was filled with remains to within 6 feet (1.8 m) of the top, the remainder were thrown into the Ganges.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Historians have given many reasons for this act of cruelty.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] With Company forces approaching Cawnpore, some believed that they would not advance if there were no hostages to save.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Or perhaps it was to ensure that no information was leaked after the fall of Cawnpore.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Other historians have suggested that the killings were an attempt to undermine Nana Sahib's relationship with the British.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Perhaps it was due to fear, the fear of being recognised by some of the prisoners for having taken part in the earlier firings.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The killing of the women and children hardened British attitudes against the sepoys.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British public was aghast, and the anti-Imperial and pro-Indian proponents lost all of their support.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Cawnpore became a war cry for the British and their allies for the rest of the conflict.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Nana Sahib disappeared near the end of the rebellion, and it is not known what happened to him.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] At the nearby town of Fatehpur, a mob had attacked and murdered the local British population.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On this pretext, Neill ordered all villages beside the Grand Trunk Road to be burned and their inhabitants to be hanged.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Neill's methods were "ruthless and horrible", and far from intimidating the population, may well have induced previously undecided sepoys and communities to revolt.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Neill was killed in action at Lucknow on 26 September and was never called to account for his punitive measures, though contemporary British sources lionised him and his "gallant blue caps".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] When the British retook Cawnpore, the soldiers took their sepoy prisoners to the Bibighar and forced them to lick the bloodstains from the walls and floor.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] They then hanged or "blew from the cannon", the traditional Mughal punishment for mutiny, the majority of the sepoy prisoners.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Although some claimed the sepoys took no actual part in the killings themselves, they did not act to stop it and this was acknowledged by Captain Thompson after the British departed Cawnpore for a second time.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Very soon after the events at Meerut, rebellion erupted in the state of Awadh (also known as Oudh, in modern-day Uttar Pradesh), which had been annexed barely a year before.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British Commissioner resident at Lucknow, Sir Henry Lawrence, had enough time to fortify his position inside the Residency compound.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The defenders, including loyal sepoys, numbered some 1700 men.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The rebels' assaults were unsuccessful, so they began a barrage of artillery and musket fire into the compound.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Lawrence was one of the first casualties.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] He was succeeded by John Eardley Inglis.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The rebels tried to breach the walls with explosives and bypass them via tunnels that led to underground close combat.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After 90 days of siege, the defenders were reduced to 300 loyal sepoys, 350 British soldiers and 550 non-combatants.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] This became known as 'The First Relief of Lucknow', as this force was not strong enough to break the siege or extricate themselves, and so was forced to join the garrison.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In October, another larger army under the new Commander-in-Chief, Sir Colin Campbell, was finally able to relieve the garrison and on 18 November, they evacuated the defended enclave within the city, the women and children leaving first.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] They then conducted an orderly withdrawal, firstly to Alambagh 4 miles (6.4 km) north where a force of 4,000 were left to construct a fort, then to Cawnpore, where they defeated an attempt by Tantia Tope to recapture the city in the Second Battle of Cawnpore.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In March 1858, Campbell once again advanced on Lucknow with a large army, meeting up with the force at Alambagh, this time seeking to suppress the rebellion in Awadh.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] He was aided by a large Nepalese contingent advancing from the north under Jung Bahadur Kunwar Rana.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] General Dhir Shamsher Kunwar Rana, the youngest brother of Jung Bahadur, also led the Nepalese forces in various parts of India including Lucknow, Benares and Patna.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Campbell's advance was slow and methodical, with a force under General Outram crossing the river on cask bridges on 4 March to enable them to fire artillery in flank.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Campbell drove the large but disorganised rebel army from Lucknow with the final fighting taking place on 21 March.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] There were few casualties to Campbell's own troops, but his cautious movements allowed large numbers of the rebels to disperse into Awadh.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Campbell was forced to spend the summer and autumn dealing with scattered pockets of resistance while losing men to heat, disease and guerrilla actions.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Jhansi State was a Maratha-ruled princely state in Bundelkhand.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] When the Raja of Jhansi died without a biological male heir in 1853, it was annexed to the British Raj by the Governor-General of India under the doctrine of lapse.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] His widow Rani Lakshmi Bai, the Rani of Jhansi, protested against the denial of rights of their adopted son.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] When war broke out, Jhansi quickly became a centre of the rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] A small group of Company officials and their families took refuge in Jhansi Fort, and the Rani negotiated their evacuation.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] However, when they left the fort they were massacred by the rebels over whom the Rani had no control; the British suspected the Rani of complicity, despite her repeated denials.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] By the end of June 1857, the company had lost control of much of Bundelkhand and eastern Rajputana.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Bengal Army units in the area, having rebelled, marched to take part in the battles for Delhi and Cawnpore.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The many princely states that made up this area began warring amongst themselves.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In September and October 1857, the Rani led the successful defence of Jhansi against the invading armies of the neighbouring rajas of Datia and Orchha.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On 3 February, Sir Hugh Rose broke the 3-month siege of Saugor.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Thousands of local villagers welcomed him as a liberator, freeing them from rebel occupation.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In March 1858, the Central India Field Force, led by Sir Hugh Rose, advanced on and laid siege to Jhansi.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Company forces captured the city, but the Rani fled in disguise.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After being driven from Jhansi and Kalpi, on 1 June 1858 Rani Lakshmi Bai and a group of Maratha rebels captured the fortress city of Gwalior from the Scindia rulers, who were British allies.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] This might have reinvigorated the rebellion, but the Central India Field Force very quickly advanced against the city.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Rani died on 17 June, the second day of the Battle of Gwalior, probably killed by a carbine shot from the 8th King's Royal Irish Hussars according to the account of three independent Indian representatives.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Company forces recaptured Gwalior within the next three days.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In descriptions of the scene of her last battle, she was compared to Joan of Arc by some commentators.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Colonel Henry Marion Durand, the then-Company resident at Indore, had brushed away any possibility of uprising in Indore.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] However, on 1 July, sepoys in Holkar's army revolted and opened fire on the cavalry pickets of the Bhopal Contingent (a locally raised force with British officers).
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] When Colonel Travers rode forward to charge, the Bhopal Cavalry refused to follow.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Bhopal Infantry also refused orders and instead levelled their guns at British sergeants and officers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Since all possibility of mounting an effective deterrent was lost, Durand decided to gather up all the British residents and escape, although 39 British residents of Indore were killed.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The rebellion in Bihar was mainly concentrated in the Western regions of the state; however, there were also some outbreaks of plundering and looting in Gaya district.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] One of the central figures was Kunwar Singh, the 80-year-old Rajput Zamindar of Jagdishpur (Bhojpur district), whose estate was in the process of being sequestrated by the Revenue Board, instigated and assumed the leadership of revolt in Bihar.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] His efforts were supported by his brother Babu Amar Singh and his commander-in-chief Hare Krishna Singh.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On 25 July, mutiny erupted in the garrisons of Danapur.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Mutinying sepoys from the 7th, 8th and 40th regiments of Bengal Native Infantry quickly moved towards the city of Arrah and were joined by Kunwar Singh and his men.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Boyle, a British railway engineer in Arrah, had already prepared an outbuilding on his property for defence against such attacks.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] As the rebels approached Arrah, all British residents took refuge at Mr.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] A siege soon ensued – eighteen civilians and 50 loyal sepoys from the Bengal Military Police Battalion under the command of Herwald Wake, the local magistrate, defended the house against artillery and musketry fire from an estimated 2000 to 3000 mutineers and rebels.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On 29 July 400 men were sent out from Danapur to relieve Arrah, but this force was ambushed by the rebels around a mile away from the siege house, severely defeated, and driven back.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On 30 July, Major Vincent Eyre, who was going up the river with his troops and guns, reached Buxar and heard about the siege.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] He immediately disembarked his guns and troops (the 5th Fusiliers) and started marching towards Arrah, disregarding direct orders not to do so.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On 2 August, some 6 miles (9.7 km) short of Arrah, the Major was ambushed by the mutineers and rebels.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After an intense fight, the 5th Fusiliers charged and stormed the rebel positions successfully.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On 3 August, Major Eyre and his men reached the siege house and successfully ended the siege.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After receiving reinforcements, Major Eyre pursued Kunwar Singh to his palace in Jagdispur; however, Singh had left by the time Eyre's forces arrived.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Eyre then proceeded to destroy the palace and the homes of Singh's brothers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In addition to Kunwar Singh's efforts, there were also rebellions carried out by Hussain Baksh Khan, Ghulam Ali Khan and Fateh Singh among others in Gaya, Nawada and Jehanabad districts.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In Barkagarh estate of South Bihar (now in Jharkhand), a major rebellion was led by Thakur Vishwanath Shahdeo who was part of the Nagavanshi dynasty.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] He was motivated by disputes he had with the Christian Kol tribals who had been grabbing his land and were implicitly supported by the British authorities.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The rebels in South Bihar asked him to lead them and he readily accepted this offer.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] He organised a *Mukti Vahini* (Liberation Regiment) with the assistance of nearby zamindars including Pandey Ganpat Rai and Nadir Ali Khan.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] What was then referred to by the British as the Punjab was a very large administrative division, centred on Lahore.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] It included not only the present-day Indian and Pakistani Punjabi regions but also the North West Frontier districts bordering Afghanistan.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Much of the region had been the Sikh Empire, ruled by Ranjit Singh until his death in 1839.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The empire had then fallen into disorder, with court factions and the Khalsa (Orthodox Sikhs) contending for power at the Lahore Durbar (court).
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After two Anglo-Sikh Wars, the entire region was annexed by the East India Company in 1849.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In 1857, the region still contained the highest numbers of both British and Indian troops.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The inhabitants of the Punjab were not as sympathetic to the sepoys as they were elsewhere in India, which limited many of the outbreaks in the Punjab to disjointed uprisings by regiments of sepoys isolated from each other.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In some garrisons, notably Firozpur, indecision on the part of the senior British officers allowed the sepoys to rebel, but the sepoys then left the area, mostly heading for Delhi.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] At the most important garrison, that of Peshawar close to the Afghan frontier, many comparatively junior officers ignored their nominal commander, General Reed, and took decisive action.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] They intercepted the sepoys' mail, thus preventing their coordinating an uprising, and formed a force known as the "Punjab Movable Column" to move rapidly to suppress any revolts as they occurred.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] When it became clear from the intercepted correspondence that some of the sepoys at Peshawar were on the point of open revolt, the four most disaffected Bengal Native regiments were disarmed by the two British infantry regiments in the cantonment, backed by artillery, on 22 May.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] This decisive act induced many local chieftains to side with the British.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Jhelum in Punjab saw a mutiny of native troops against the British.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Here 35 British soldiers of Her Majesty's 24th Regiment of Foot (South Wales Borderers) were killed by mutineers on 7 July 1857.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Among the dead was Captain Francis Spring, the eldest son of Colonel William Spring.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] John's Church Jhelum was built and the names of those 35 British soldiers are carved on a marble lectern present in that church.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The final large-scale military uprising in the Punjab took place on 9 July, when most of a brigade of sepoys at Sialkot rebelled and began to move to Delhi.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] They were intercepted by John Nicholson with an equal British force as they tried to cross the Ravi River.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After fighting steadily but unsuccessfully for several hours, the sepoys tried to fall back across the river but became trapped on an island.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Three days later, Nicholson annihilated the 1,100 trapped sepoys in the Battle of Trimmu Ghat.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British had been recruiting irregular units from Sikh and Pashtun communities even before the first unrest among the Bengal units, and the numbers of these were greatly increased during the rebellion, 34,000 fresh levies eventually being pressed into service.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] At one stage, faced with the need to send troops to reinforce the besiegers of Delhi, the Commissioner of the Punjab (Sir John Lawrence) suggested handing the coveted prize of Peshawar to Dost Mohammad Khan of Afghanistan in return for a pledge of friendship.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British agents in Peshawar and the adjacent districts were horrified.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Referring to the massacre of a retreating British Army in 1842, Herbert Edwardes wrote, "Dost Mahomed would not be a mortal Afghan ... if he did not assume our day to be gone in India and follow after us as an enemy.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] British cannot retreat – Kabul would come again." In the event Lord Canning insisted on Peshawar being held, and Dost Mohammad, whose relations with Britain had been equivocal for over 20 years, remained neutral.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In September 1857 Rai Ahmad Khan Kharal, head of the Kharal tribe, led an insurrection in the Neeli Bar and Sandal Bar, between the Sutlej, Ravi and Chenab rivers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The rebels held the forests of Gogaira and had some initial successes against the British forces in the area, besieging Major Crawford Chamberlain at Chichawatni.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] A squadron of Punjabi cavalry sent by Sir John Lawrence raised the siege.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Ahmed Khan was killed but the insurgents found a new leader in Mahr Bahawal Fatyana, who maintained the uprising for three months until Government forces penetrated the jungle and scattered the rebel tribesmen.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In September 1857, sepoys took control of the treasury in Chittagong.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The treasury remained under rebel control for several days.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Further mutinies on 18 November saw the 2nd, 3rd and 4th companies of the 34th Bengal Infantry Regiment storming the Chittagong Jail and releasing all prisoners.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The mutineers were eventually suppressed by the Gurkha regiments.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The mutiny also spread to Kolkata and later Dhaka, the former Mughal capital of Bengal.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Residents in the city's Lalbagh area were kept awake at night by the rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Sepoys joined hands with the common populace in Jalpaiguri to take control of the city's cantonment.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In January 1858, many sepoys received shelter from the royal family of the princely state of Hill Tippera.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The interior areas of Bengal proper were already experiencing growing resistance to Company rule due to the Muslim Faraizi movement.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In central and north Gujarat, the rebellion was sustained by landowner jagirdars, taluqdar and thakurs with the support of armed communities of Bhil, Koli, Pathans and Arabs, unlike the mutiny by sepoys in north India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Their main opposition of British was due to Inam commission.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Bet Dwarka island, along with Okhamandal region of Kathiawar peninsula which was under the Gaekwad of Baroda State, saw a revolt by the Waghers in January 1858 who, by July 1859, controlled that region.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In October 1859, a joint offensive by British, Gaekwad and other princely states troops ousted the rebels and recaptured the region.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] During the rebellion, Surendra Sai was one of the many people broken out of Hazaribagh jail by mutineers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In the middle of September Surendra established himself in Sambalpur's old fort.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] He quickly organised a meeting with the Assistant Commissioner (Captain Leigh), and Leigh agreed to ask the government to cancel his and his brother's imprisonment while Surendra dispersed his followers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] This agreement was soon broken, however, when on 31 September escaped the town and make for Khinda, where his brother was located with a 1,400-man force.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British quickly moved to send two companies from the 40th Madras Native Infantry from Cuttack on 10 October, and after a forced march reached Khinda on 5 November, only to find the place abandoned as the rebels retreated to the jungle.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Much of the country of Sambalpur was under the rebels' control, and they maintained a hit and run guerrilla war for quite some time.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In December the British made further preparations to crush the uprising in Sambalpur, and it was temporarily transferred from the Chota Nagpur Division into the Orissa Division of the Bengal Presidency.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On the 30th a major battle was fought in which Surendra's brother was killed and the mutineers were routed.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In January the British achieved minor successes, capturing a few major villages like Kolabira, and in February calm began to be restored.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] However, Surendra still held out, and the jungle hampered British parties from capturing him.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Additionally, any native daring to collaborate with the British were terrorized along with their family.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] After a new policy that promised amnesty for mutineers, Surendra surrendered in May 1862.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In September 1857, Shamli, then a tahsil of Muzaffarnagar district in the North-Western Provinces (now Uttar Pradesh), witnessed a local uprising during the Indian Rebellion of 1857.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Chaudhary Mohar Singh, a Jat zamindar of Maulaheri, led villagers and allied groups in attacking the tahsil headquarters, setting fire to government offices and briefly seizing control of the town.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The action disrupted British administration and supply routes in the region.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] British troops subsequently recaptured Shamli, and executed Mohar Singh.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Contemporary colonial accounts describe his body being displayed publicly as a warning to others.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The authorities in British colonies with an Indian population, sepoy or civilian, took measures to secure themselves against copycat uprisings.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In the Straits Settlements and Trinidad the annual Hosay processions were banned, riots broke out in penal settlements in Burma and the Settlements, in Penang the loss of a musket provoked a near riot, and security was boosted especially in locations with an Indian convict population.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Both sides committed atrocities against civilians.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In Oudh alone, some estimates put the toll at 150,000 Indians killed during the war, with 100,000 of them being civilians.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The capture of Delhi, Allahabad, Kanpur and Lucknow by British forces were followed by general massacres.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Another notable atrocity was carried out by General Neill who massacred thousands of Indian mutineers and Indian civilians suspected of supporting the rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The rebels' murder of British women, children and wounded soldiers (including sepoys who sided with the British) at Cawnpore, and the subsequent printing of the events in the British papers, left many British soldiers outraged and seeking revenge.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Aside from hanging mutineers, the British had some "blown from cannon", (an old Mughal punishment adopted many years before in India), in which sentenced rebels were tied over the mouths of cannons and blown to pieces when the cannons were fired.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] A particular act of cruelty on the part of the British troops at Cawnpore included forcing many Muslim or Hindu rebels to eat pork or beef, as well as licking buildings freshly stained with blood of the dead before subsequent public hangings.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Most of the British press, outraged by the stories of alleged rape committed by the rebels against British women, as well as the killings of British civilians and wounded British soldiers, did not advocate clemency of any kind towards the Indian population.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Governor General Canning ordered moderation in dealing with native sensibilities and earned the scornful sobriquet "Clemency Canning" from the press and later parts of the British public.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In terms of sheer numbers, the casualties were much higher on the Indian side.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] From the end of 1857, the British had begun to gain ground again.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On 8 July 1858, a peace treaty was signed, and the rebellion ended.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The last rebels were defeated in Gwalior on 20 June 1858.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] By 1859, rebel leaders Bakht Khan and Nana Sahib had either been slain or had fled.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Some British troops adopted a policy of "no prisoners".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] One officer, Thomas Lowe, remembered how on one occasion his unit had taken 76 prisoners – they were just too tired to carry on killing and needed a rest, he recalled.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Later, after a quick trial, the prisoners were lined up with a British soldier standing a couple of yards in front of them.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On the order "fire", they were all simultaneously shot, "swept... from their earthly existence".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The aftermath of the rebellion has been the focus of new work using Indian sources and population studies.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Approximately 6,000 of the 40,000 British living in India were killed.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The scale of the punishments handed out by the British "Army of Retribution" was considered largely appropriate and justified in a Britain shocked by embellished reports of atrocities carried out against British troops and civilians by the rebels.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Accounts of the time frequently reach the "hyperbolic register", according to Christopher Herbert, especially in the often-repeated claim that the "Red Year" of 1857 marked "a terrible break" in British experience.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Such was the atmosphere – a national "mood of retribution and despair" that led to "almost universal approval" of the measures taken to pacify the revolt.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Incidents of rape allegedly committed by Indian rebels against British women and girls appalled the British public.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] These atrocities were often used to justify the British reaction to the rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] British newspapers printed various eyewitness accounts of the rape of English women and girls.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] One such account was published by *The Times*, regarding an incident where 48 English girls as young as 10 had been raped by Indian rebels in Delhi.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Karl Marx criticized this story as false propaganda, and pointed out that the story was written by a clergyman in Bangalore, far from the events of the rebellion, with no evidence to support his allegation.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Individual incidents captured the public's interest and were heavily reported by the press.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] One such incident was that of General Wheeler's daughter Margaret being forced to live as her captor's concubine, though this was reported to the Victorian public as Margaret killing her rapist then herself.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Another version of the story suggested that Margaret had been killed after her abductor had argued with his wife over her.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] During the aftermath of the rebellion, a series of exhaustive investigations were carried out by British police and intelligence officials into reports that British women prisoners had been "dishonoured" at the Bibighar and elsewhere.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] One such detailed enquiry was at the direction of Lord Canning.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The consensus was that there was no convincing evidence of such crimes having been committed, although numbers of British women and children had been killed outright.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The term 'Sepoy' or 'Sepoyism' became a derogatory term for nationalists, especially in Ireland.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Bahadur Shah II was arrested at Humayun's Tomb and tried for treason by a military commission assembled at Delhi and exiled to Rangoon where he died in 1862, bringing the Mughal dynasty to an end.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In 1877 Queen Victoria took the title of Empress of India on the advice of Prime Minister Benjamin Disraeli.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The rebellion saw the end of the East India Company's rule in India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In August, by the Government of India Act 1858, the company's ruling powers over India were transferred to the British Crown.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] A new British government department, the India Office, was created to handle the governance of India, and its head, the Secretary of State for India, was entrusted with formulating Indian policy.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Governor-General of India gained a new title, Viceroy of India, and implemented the policies devised by the India Office.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Some former East India Company territories, such as the Straits Settlements, became colonies in their own right.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British colonial administration embarked on a program of reform, trying to integrate Indian higher castes and rulers into the government and abolishing attempts at Westernization.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Viceroy stopped land grabs, decreed religious tolerance and admitted Indians into civil service, albeit mainly as subordinates.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Essentially the old East India Company bureaucracy remained, though there was a major shift in attitudes.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In looking for the causes of the Rebellion the authorities alighted on two things: religion and the economy.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On religion it was felt that there had been too much interference with indigenous traditions, both Hindu and Muslim.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On the economy it was now believed that the previous attempts by the company to introduce free market competition had undermined traditional power structures and bonds of loyalty placing the peasantry at the mercy of merchants and moneylenders.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In consequence the new British Raj was constructed in part around a conservative agenda, based on a preservation of tradition and hierarchy.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] On a political level it was also felt that the previous lack of consultation between rulers and ruled had been another significant factor in contributing to the uprising.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In consequence, Indians were drawn into government at a local level.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Though this was on a limited scale a crucial precedent had been set, with the creation of a new 'white collar' Indian elite, further stimulated by the opening of universities at Calcutta, Bombay and Madras, a result of the Indian Universities Act.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] So, alongside the values of traditional and ancient India, a new professional middle class was starting to arise, in no way bound by the values of the past.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Acting on these sentiments, Lord Ripon, viceroy from 1880 to 1885, extended the powers of local self-government and sought to remove racial practices in the law courts by the Ilbert Bill.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] But a policy at once liberal and progressive at one turn was reactionary and backward at the next, creating new elites and confirming old attitudes.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Ilbert Bill had the effect only of causing a white mutiny and the end of the prospect of perfect equality before the law.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In 1886 measures were adopted to restrict Indian entry into the civil service.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Bengal Army dominated the Presidency armies before 1857 and a direct result after the rebellion was the scaling back of the size of the Bengali contingent in the army.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Brahmin presence in the Bengal Army was reduced because of their perceived primary role as mutineers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British looked for increased recruitment in the Punjab for the Bengal army as a result of the apparent discontent that resulted in the Sepoy conflict.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The rebellion transformed both the native and British armies of British India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] Of the 74 regular Bengal Native Infantry regiments in existence at the beginning of 1857, only twelve escaped mutiny or disbandment.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] All ten of the Bengal Light Cavalry regiments were lost.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The old Bengal Army had accordingly almost completely vanished from the order of battle.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] These troops were replaced by new units recruited from castes hitherto under-utilised by the British and from the minority so-called "Martial Races", such as the Sikhs and the Gurkhas.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The inefficiencies of the old organisation, which had estranged sepoys from their British officers, were addressed, and the post-1857 units were mainly organised on the "irregular" system.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] From 1797 until the rebellion of 1857, each regular Bengal Native Infantry regiment had had 22 or 23 British officers, who held every position of authority down to the second-in-command of each company.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In irregular units there were fewer British officers, but they associated themselves far more closely with their soldiers, while more responsibility was given to the Indian officers.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The British increased the ratio of British to Indian soldiers within India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] From 1861 Indian artillery was replaced by British units, except for a few mountain batteries.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The post-rebellion changes formed the basis of the military organisation of British India until the early 20th century.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The Indian Order of Merit was the only gallantry medal available to Native soldiers between 1837 and 1907.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] There is no universally agreed name for the events of this period.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] In India and Pakistan, it has been termed as the "War of Independence of 1857" or "First War of Indian Independence" but it is not uncommon to use terms such as the "Revolt of 1857".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The classification of the Rebellion being "First War of Independence" is not without its critics in India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] The use of the term "Indian Mutiny" is considered by some Indian politicians as belittling the importance of what happened and therefore reflecting an imperialistic attitude.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p02] "The Indian Insurrection" was a name used in the press of the UK and British colonies at the time.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Michael Adas (1971) examines the historiography with emphasis on the four major approaches: the Indian nationalist view; the Marxist analysis; the view of the Rebellion as a traditionalist rebellion; and intensive studies of local uprisings.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Many of the key primary and secondary sources appear in Biswamoy Pati, ed.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Metcalf has stressed the importance of the work by Cambridge professor Eric Stokes (1924–1981), especially Stokes' *The Peasant and the Raj: Studies in Agrarian Society and Peasant Rebellion in Colonial India* (1978).
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Metcalf says Stokes undermines the assumption that 1857 was a response to general causes emanating from entire classes of people.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Instead, Stokes argues that 1) those Indians who suffered the greatest relative deprivation rebelled and that 2) the decisive factor in precipitating a revolt was the presence of prosperous magnates who supported British rule.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Stokes also explores issues of economic development, the nature of privileged landholding, the role of moneylenders, the usefulness of classical rent theory, and, especially, the notion of the "rich peasant".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Wagner, who has conducted the most recent survey of the literature, modern Indian historiography is yet to move beyond responding to the "prejudice" of colonial accounts.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Wagner sees no reason why atrocities committed by Indians should be understated or inflated merely because these things "offend our post-colonial sensibilities".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Wagner also stresses the importance of William Dalrymple's *The Last Mughal: The Fall of a Dynasty, Delhi 1857*.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Dalrymple was assisted by Mahmood Farooqui, who translated key Urdu and Shikastah sources and published a selection in *Besieged: Voices from Delhi 1857*.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Dalrymple emphasized the role of religion and explored in detail the internal divisions and politico-religious discord amongst the rebels.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] He did not discover much in the way of proto-nationalism or any of the roots of modern India in the rebellion.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Sabbaq Ahmed has looked at the ways in which ideologies of royalism, militarism, and Jihad influenced the behaviour of contending Muslim factions.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Almost from the moment the first sepoys mutinied in Meerut, the nature and the scope of the Indian Rebellion of 1857 has been contested and argued over.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Speaking in the House of Commons in July 1857, Benjamin Disraeli labelled it a 'national revolt' while Lord Palmerston, the Prime Minister, tried to downplay the scope and the significance of the event as a 'mere military mutiny'.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Reflecting this debate, an early historian of the rebellion, Charles Ball, used the word mutiny in his title, but labelled it a "struggle for liberty and independence as a people" in the text.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Historians remain divided on whether the rebellion can properly be considered a war of Indian independence or not, although it is popularly considered to be one in India.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] A second school of thought while acknowledging the validity of the above-mentioned arguments opines that this rebellion may indeed be called a war of India's independence.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] The Government of India celebrated the year 2007 as the 150th anniversary of "India's First War of Independence".
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Several books written by Indian authors were released in the anniversary year including Amresh Mishra's "War of Civilizations", a controversial history of the Rebellion of 1857, and "Recalcitrance" by Anurag Kumar, one of the few novels written in English by an Indian based on the events of 1857.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] In 2007, a group of retired British soldiers and civilians, some of them descendants of British soldiers who died in the conflict, attempted to visit the site of the Siege of Lucknow.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Fears of violence by Indian demonstrators, supported by the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, prevented the British visitors from visiting the site.
[src:asia/1857-revolt-p03] Despite the protests, Sir Mark Havelock was able to make his way past police to visit the grave of his ancestor, General Henry Havelock.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] From 15 June to October 2022, floods in Pakistan killed 1,739 people, and caused about US$40 billion in damage.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The immediate causes of the floods were heavier than usual monsoon rains and melting glaciers that followed a severe heat wave, both of which are linked to climate change.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] On 25 August 2022, Pakistan declared a state of emergency because of the flooding.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The flooding was the world's deadliest flood since the 2020 South Asian floods and described as the worst in the country's history.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] It was also recorded as one of the costliest natural disasters in world history.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The minister of climate change of Pakistan, Sherry Rehman, said that the provinces of Sindh and Balochistan had received more rainfall than the August average, with 784% and 500% more, respectively.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Higher than average monsoon rains were also recorded in India and Bangladesh.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The Indian Ocean is one of the fastest warming oceans in the world, warming by an average of 1 °C (1.8 °F) (while worldwide temperatures are now at 1.2 °C (2.2 °F) above pre-industrial temperatures, oceans in general are at around 0.7 °C (1.3 °F)).
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The rise in sea surface temperatures is believed to increase monsoon rainfall.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In addition, southern Pakistan experienced back-to-back heat waves in May and June, which were record-setting and themselves made more likely by climate change.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] These created a strong thermal low that brought heavier rains than usual.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The heatwaves also triggered glacial flooding in Gilgit-Baltistan.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Pakistan contributes less than 1% of global greenhouse gas emissions, but is one of the places most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] A study by an international team of climate scientists says that global heating made the flooding up to 50% worse and future floods more likely.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] However, some of the contributors to the severity of the flooding are local to the country.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Unregulated construction and deforestation in Pakistan are factors that have worsened the floods.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 1,739 people died, including 647 children, and an additional 12,867 were injured.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Over 2.1 million people were left homeless because of the floods.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] These are the deadliest floods in Pakistan since 2010, when nearly 2,000 died in flooding, and the deadliest in the world since the 2020 South Asian floods.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] On 29 August, Sherry Rehman, the minister of climate change, claimed that "one-third" of the country was underwater, and there was "no dry land to pump the water out", adding that it was a "crisis of unimaginable proportions".
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Her claim received widespread media coverage.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In contrast, the UNOSAT United Nations Satellite Centre reported that 75,000km2 had been flooded (around 9% of Pakistan) with USAID stating a maximum floodwater extent of 32,800 square miles (around 10% of Pakistan).
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] A BBC report estimated that around 10–12% of Pakistan was flooded; the total area of standing floodwaters peaked between July and August at approximately 32,800 square miles (84,952 km2).
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Agricultural fields were also devastated by the flooding.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The floods affected 33 million people in Pakistan and destroyed 897,014 houses and damaged another 1,391,467.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 1,164,270 livestock have been killed, most of them in the province of Balochistan, while destruction to 13,115 kilometres (8,149 mi) of roads and 439 bridges has impeded access across flood-affected areas.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Over 22,000 schools were damaged or destroyed.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The Ministry of Finance estimated the damage of the flooding was ₨3.91 trillion (US$14.9 billion), and the economic loss was ₨3.99 trillion (US$15.2 billion).
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The government required ₨4.26 trillion (US$16.3 billion) to recover from the flooding.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) and the International Labour Organization (ILO) also concurred with the damage and the economic loss assessed by the government of Pakistan.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] However, another assessment done by the World Bank and the Pakistan Climate Change Council claimed that the damage of the flooding stood at US$40 billion.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] As a result of the devastating superfoods in these areas, nearly 8 million displaced as their houses and properties were wiped away by the monsoon rains, floods and landslides in 2022.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In this displacement, a sizable population of women was affected and were compelled to seek refuge and live in camps made of plastic tents exposed to the risk of gender based Violence (GBV).
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] A reported number of 650,000 pregnant women was affected in these far-flung rural areas with already scarce resources for healthcare.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The data shows a striking number of 73, 000 full term pregnant women, who were expected to give birth within a month living in an environment highly conducive of gastric and waterborne diseases posing threat to their situation.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Due to the floods more than 1,500 healthcare facilities were partially or completely destroyed.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Many of these women gave birth in the make-shift temporary health camps where administering operations and securing vaccines for the newly born children was a challenge for the health workers.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Aid workers warned that lack of clean drinking water caused an increase in waterborne diseases, namely diarrhea, cholera, dengue, and malaria.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Skin infections caused by wet conditions have also been widely reported.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Floods in Sindh killed 799 people and injured 8,422.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Among the 338 children killed were three who died when the roof of their house collapsed in Kandhkot.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 10 million people were displaced in Sindh and 57,496 houses were severely damaged or completely destroyed, mostly in the Hyderabad Division, and 830 cattle were killed.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 6,200 km2 (1,540,000 acres) of farmland was impacted by the floods.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The Larkana and Sukkur divisions were severely affected by the floods; Thari Mirwah and Khairpur Nathan Shah were "inundated".
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The floods turned the Indus River into a lake 100 km (62 mi) wide.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The towns of Johi and Mehar were saved by their residents making ring bands around their towns.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In Jacobabad, which has been called the world's hottest city, more than 40,000 people were living in temporary shelters with limited access to food, with 19 dead from the flooding as of 31 August.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] During the floods, Lake Manchar overflowed, and in September 2022 efforts were made to assist its drainage.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In the Dadu District, floodwater reportedly submerged 300 villages.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The Sindh provincial government confirmed, on 16 September 2022, 588 cases of malaria, with a further 10,604 suspected cases, as well as 17,977 cases of diarrhea, and 20,064 of skin disease.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Since 1 July, a total of 2,300,000 patients have been treated for malaria in field and mobile hospitals.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] A high of 90,000 cases of diarrhea were reported in a single day on 1 September.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Flooding in Balochistan killed 336 people.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In many areas, rainwater infiltrated many homes and made them uninhabitable.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 426,897 houses were either damaged or completely destroyed, and 1,230 km2 (304,000 acres) of crops were lost.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] An estimated half-million livestock were also killed.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] According to the Relief Commissioner Provincial Disaster Management Authority, Balochistan's capital Quetta was declared a disaster area due to rains, and an emergency was declared in the province.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Many organisations took part in relief, including Balochistan Youth Action Committee & Apna Dastarkhwan (Zariya Social Welfare Foundation).
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 309 people died and 600,000 others were displaced by floods in the province.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Among them were five children in Upper Dir District; they had been returning home from school when they were swept away by the floods and drowned.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 326,897 houses were damaged due to floods and landslides, and 7,742 cattle died from collapsing sheds.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In Swat District, a newly built hotel collapsed due to excessive flooding.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The southwestern part of the province was previously affected by the June 2022 Afghanistan earthquake.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In Lower Kohistan District, 5 people stranded in a hill torrent were swept away; 4 of them were killed, while one was rescued.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In Balakot, 8 nomads were killed due to flooding in a tributary of the Kunhar River.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 12 people were also killed in flooding in different areas of Dera Ismail Khan due to flash floods from hill torrents.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 23 people died, four were missing, and floods badly affected the Karakoram Highway.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Roads were closed for traffic at several places due to landslides.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The districts of Ghizer, Nagar, Diamer, Ghanche, and Astore were the worst affected.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 420 homes were destroyed and 740 were damaged due to floods and landslides.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Meanwhile, the S-1 Strategic Highway also suffered erosion due to high water flows in the Indus River.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The Ishkoman Valley Road was cut off at Gutkash due to flooding in the Ishkoman River.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] A bridge at Chhorbat in Ghanche District was also flooded.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Valley roads and two bridges in Nagar District were swept away by floods.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] There were also reports of damage in Khanar and Bonar in Diamer District.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] As of 26 August, most parts of the villages in Ghizer were destroyed by the flood.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Among these were Buber Valley, Gahkuch, and Gulmuti.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Residents were asked to evacuate the flood-affected areas as river levels rose to an extremely dangerous height.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In Punjab, 223 people died and 3,858 others suffered injuries.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In Taunsa, many settlements were submerged in floodwater.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In the historical town of Mangadotha, west of Taunsa, hundreds of houses and livestock were swept away by flood waters.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 7,200 km2 (1,780,000 acres) of crops and orchids were also impacted.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Residents of communities adjacent to flooded rivers began to evacuate, with most families moving away.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Most of the families have moved to safer places on foot and camels while carrying only essential supplies as roads and bridges were washed away.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 48 people died by flooding in Azad Kashmir.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] On 31 July, in Poonch District, ten people died and four were injured when a roof collapsed on top of them.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Five tourists from Mianwali were swept away and later confirmed to have been killed in Neelum Valley on 19 August.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The prime minister, Shehbaz Sharif, who had decided to spearhead the relief operations in the wake of massive floods, met international partners on 25 August who pledged to provide $500 million to the country to mitigate the havoc wreaked by flooding.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Army officers, federal cabinet members, and senators will donate their one-month salary for the flood relief fund.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] PTCL Group, Pakistan's largest telecom and internet services provider, announced ₨.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 1.75 billion(or US$8 million) to support flood relief efforts and those affected by the floods.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The chairman of the Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf (PTI) party and former prime minister, Imran Khan, held a 3-hour-long telethon to raise funds for flood victims and received ₨.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 500 crores (or US$22.5 million) in pledges for flood relief.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] On 30 August, the Government of Pakistan announced $170 million allocation to flood victims, which will be disbursed through the Benazir Income Support Programme (BISP) as part of Pakistan Flood Response Plan 2022.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The Pakistani embassies in China and Turkey have also set up fundraisers requesting flood relief donations from locals.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Pakistan Telecommunication Authority (PTA) introduced the 9999 SMS code for flood relief donations to enable consumers to donate their funds through mobile phone text to support the flood victims.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The consumers would be required to write "fund" and send it to the 9999 short code to donate ₨.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] 10 (or US ¢4.5) to contribute to the prime minister's floods relief fund.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The government has been accused of inaction on relief and rescue operations, with local officials allegedly hoarding humanitarian aid.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Incidents of looting due to lack of aid have emerged, with several NGOs halting relief operations after their trucks carrying relief goods were looted.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] In Sukkur, police booked 100 flood-affected persons under terrorism charges for protesting against the lack of food and relief when Shehbaz Sharif and foreign minister Bilawal Bhutto visited to assess flood damage on 26 August.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Mehraz provided free low-cost housing designs made of bamboo for affected communities, focusing on environmentally friendly and resilient construction techniques and flood management.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Following the immediate relief phase, Pakistan established the National Flood Response and Coordination Centre (NFRCC) to coordinate rehabilitation efforts.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The government launched a cash relief program disbursing PKR 37.2 billion to 1.5 million affected families through the Benazir Income Support Programme (BISP).
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The international community praised Pakistan's coordination efforts.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] UN agencies reached 7.5 million people with food, water, shelter, and health services, with 60% of the $816 million appeal funded.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Community Emergency Response Teams (CERTs) played a critical role in rescue operations, evacuating over 9,000 people.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Notably, 36% of search and rescue volunteers were women, demonstrating significant community participation.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Pakistan launched climate-resilient reconstruction initiatives, including the "Living Indus" project.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The UNDP supported construction of 800 climate-resilient homes and livelihood restoration for 200,000 people.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The floods catalyzed Pakistan's leadership in global climate advocacy.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] At COP27, Pakistan successfully championed the establishment of a Loss and Damage Fund, securing over $700 million in initial pledges from developed nations.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] On 1 August 2022, a Pakistan Army Aviation helicopter on flood relief operations in the Lasbela area of Balochistan lost contact with air traffic control.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] The six military personnel on board, including the commander of the XII Corps, Lieutenant General Sarfraz Ali, died in the crash.
[src:asia/2022-pakistan-floods] Reports from Pakistani authorities on their early investigations attributed the crash to poor weather conditions, whereas Reuters reported on unverified claims from the Baloch terrorist group "Baloch Raaji Aajoi Sangar" that they shot the helicopter down.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] From January to October 2022, excessive rainfall and widespread monsoon flooding occurred in the South Asian countries of Afghanistan, Bangladesh, India, Nepal, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] It has become the region's deadliest floods since 2020, with over 4,700 people dead.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Monsoons hit South Asia every year, mostly between June and September.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Every year, floods affect the Indian subcontinent, collapsing buildings and causing landslides.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Climate change in South Asia has exacerbated these storms.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Floods in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa killed eight people in January, however from June 2022, floods affected most of Pakistan, affecting around 33 million people, or 12% of the country's population.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Over two million houses were damaged or destroyed by flooding, and over $40 billion USD worth of damage has been caused.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] At least 1,760 people were killed by flooding, most of them in the provinces of Sindh, Balochistan, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, and Punjab.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] In May 2022, floods affected several parts of Afghanistan, killing 429 people.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] It was later reported the 182 people died due to flooding in August, as well as 40 people in July and 19 in June.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] From June to August, just as the country was recovering from an earthquake in Khost Province, floods hit again, killing 19 in June, 39 in July, and 182 others in August.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] In late May, floods have affected over 4,000 villages in the Indian states of Assam and Bihar, killing at least 186 people.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Floods continued to affect Assam in June, killing a further 200 people.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] From June to July, floods in Maharashtra killed 105 people.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] From June to August, floods have also affected the northwest of the country, killing at least 40 and leaving 13 others missing in the Indian state of Uttarakhand while 276 others died in Himachal Pradesh.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Floods have also affected the state of Odisha, killing six.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] In Gujarat, floods have killed at least 61 since June.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] On 30 June, 58 people died, 3 went missing, and 18 were injured after a landslide occurred in the Noney District of Manipur.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] On 8 July, 16 people died while 40 were missing after floods during the 2022 Amarnath Yatra in Jammu and Kashmir.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] From 18 to 23 August, a tropical storm caused floods to affect the coast of eastern India, killing 14 people.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] In September, hundreds of homes were damaged and 12 people died in floods in Uttar Pradesh, including nine from a collapsing wall.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Floods in October killed at least 18 people.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] In total, 2,035 people were killed by flooding in India throughout 2022.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Since 17 May, floods have affected parts of Bangladesh.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] At least 141 people were killed, most of them in the Sylhet Division.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] In October, Cyclone Sitrang caused an additional 35 fatalities.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Floods and landslides in the first nine months of 2022 have killed at least 70 people in Nepal.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] On 16 September, a landslide killed 22 people and left 10 missing in Achham District.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] At least 46 people were killed and 22 were left missing by heavy flooding in October, with Karnali Province being the worst affected.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] Three deaths have been reported due to floods in Sri Lanka in June, and hundreds of homes had been damaged.
[src:asia/2022-south-asian-floods] In October, an additional three deaths occurred and over 210 houses were damaged or destroyed.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The **2024 Bangladesh quota reform movement** was a series of anti-government and pro-democracy protests in Bangladesh, spearheaded primarily by university students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Initially focused on restructuring quota-based systems for government job recruitment, the movement expanded against what many perceived as an authoritarian government when government-associated groups carried out the July massacre of protesters and civilians, most of whom were students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] While it started as a student movement, the movement later escalated into a fully-fledged mass uprising known as the July Uprising.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protest began in June 2024, in response to the Supreme Court of Bangladesh reinstating a 30% quota for descendants of freedom fighters, reversing the government decision made in response to the 2018 Bangladesh quota reform movement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students began to feel like merit-based opportunities in public sector jobs would diminish.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protest quickly spread throughout the entire country because of the government's violent response, as well as growing public dissatisfaction against an oppressive government.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The situation was further complicated by many other ongoing issues, like the government's inability to manage a prolonged economic downturn, reports of rampant corruption and human rights violations, and the absence of democratic channels for initiating changes.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The government sought to suppress the protests by shutting down all educational institutions.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] They deployed their student wing, the Chhatra League, along with other factions of the Awami League party.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] These groups resorted to using firearms and sharp weapons against the demonstrators.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The government then deployed Police, RAB, BGB and other armed forces, declaring a nationwide shoot-at-sight curfew amid an unprecedented government-ordered nationwide internet and mobile connectivity blackout that effectively isolated Bangladesh from the rest of the world.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Later, the government also blocked social media in Bangladesh.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Government forces cordoned off parts of the capital city of Dhaka and conducted Block Raids, randomly picking up anyone they suspected having links to the protest, causing fear among the city residents.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] As of August 2, there were 215 confirmed deaths, more than 20,000 injuries, and more than 11,000 arrests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The unofficial death toll was between 300 and 500.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] UNICEF reported that at least 32 children were killed during July's protests, with many more injured and detained.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Determining the exact number of deaths has been difficult because the government reportedly restricted hospitals from sharing information with the media without police permission, hospital CCTV footage was confiscated, and numerous individuals with gunshot wounds were buried without identification.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The Awami League government, led by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina have suggested that political opponents have co-opted the protest.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Despite the curfew restrictions the movement remained ongoing as it expanded its demands to include accountability for violence, a ban on the student wing of the government Chhatra League, and resignation of certain government officials, including the resignation of Sheikh Hasina.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The government's use of widespread violence against the general public turned the student protests into a people's uprising known as the Non-Cooperation Movement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] After the High Court ruled in favour of quotas on 5 June 2024, the students of various universities in Dhaka united to demand quota reform.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] After the movement was initially started, it was postponed due to Eid al-Adha and the summer holidays.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] After the holidays, the agitation started again peacefully but gradually became widespread.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Initially, the students and teachers of many public universities and other educational institutions joined the movement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Later, the students of private universities also followed suit by joining the public demonstration.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Under the banner of Students Against Discrimination (Bengali: বৈষম্যবিরোধী ছাত্র আন্দোলন), students started the **Bangla Blockade**.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] During the movement, the Appellate Division issued a status quo for four weeks on 10 July, canceling the freedom fighters' quota.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Reacting to the court verdict, the students said they are seeking a final solution to the quota issue from the government, claiming the movement has nothing to do with the court.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protest also affected the domestic train and road transportation networks across Bangladesh.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Peaceful demonstrations by the students restarted on 1 July, while public university teachers declared a strike protesting the new Universal Pension Scheme, causing universities to close.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Demonstrations spread nationwide as the movement became headed by a newly formed Students Against Discrimination, an umbrella organisation for the student protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On July 7, protestors launched the nationwide Bangla Blockade, obstructing traffic and rail in major cities and metropolises including Dhaka, Chittagong, Comilla, Jessore, Rangpur, Rajshahi, and Bogra.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] While the Appellate Division ordered a four-week status quo regarding the quota on 10 July, protesters continued to demand a solution from the government.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Protests turned violent for the first time the next day as the police clashed with the students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 14 July, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina made controversial remarks about the anti-quota protests, escalating the situation and raising the public's anger.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 15 July, the ruling Awami League solidified its stance against the demonstrations, and the protestors met first violent suppression from the Chhatra League leaving several hundred injured.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In response to the Chhatra League attacks, student protesters at Rajshahi University vandalized halls, targeting the room of the President of RU Chhatra League and other members associated with the group.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protesters in the University of Dhaka removed Chhatra League members from 11 different halls and declared a ban on the pro-quota student organization.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At other universities across the country, students expelled Chhatra League members from their campuses, with some members in Chittagong even being thrown from high rooftops by angry protesters during clashes.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] These actions led to many campuses independently declaring themselves "Chhatra League Free".
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In response to the violent protests involving members of the Bangladesh Chhatra League and Bangladesh Police, the Students Against Discrimination issued a revised nine-point demand.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Home Minister Asaduzzaman Khan and Road Transport and Bridges Minister Obaidul Quader should resign from their cabinet positions and party roles for their alleged roles in using law enforcement and Chhatra League to carry out violence against the protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Deputy inspectors general of police, police commissioners, and superintendents of police in the areas where student casualties occurred must be dismissed from their posts.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The vice-chancellors and proctors of Dhaka University, Jahangirnagar University, and Rajshahi University must resign due to their inadequate response to the violence against students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] There should be a nationwide ban on the Awami League's student wing Bangladesh Chhatra League in all educational institutions in Bangladesh.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Policemen, law enforcement officers, army/military officials and any individuals involved in the attacks should be arrested and held accountable according to the laws.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Financial compensation should be provided to the families of students who were killed or injured during the protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] All educational institutions and student residential halls should be reopened immediately.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Law enforcement officers, including armed forces and other security personnel, should be withdrawn from all educational institutions to ensure a peaceful environment.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 5 June, the High Court re-established the job quota that reserves 30% of the civil service posts for the children and grandchildren of freedom fighters in the Bangladesh Liberation War.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Six universities performed peaceful protests against the quota ruling.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protests calmed down because of the Eid-ul Adha celebrations, but they soon restarted after the break.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 7 July, students staged a blockade and demanded the rescinding of the quota.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At approximately 11:00 a.m. in the University of Dhaka, a protest march commenced in front of the library, passed by the Anti Terrorism Raju Memorial Sculpture, and culminated in the blockage of the Shahbag intersection.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Members of the law and order forces positioned barricades in front of the students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In the afternoon, it is known that the status quo has been given for four weeks in the ruling given by the High Court cancelling the quota system.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The Chief Justice asked the students to go back.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Dhaka's transport system came to a standstill due to the blockade in various parts of Dhaka.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Long-distance buses and trains were stopped due to the agitation.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Police attacked protesting students of Cumilla University.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The blockade in Shahbag was supposed to start at 3:00 p.m. but due to rain, the students crossed the police barricade on their way to Shahbag and started later at 4:30 p.m.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Dhaka College students retreated due to police barricades and Dhaka University students joined the students of Jagannath University at Shahbag.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Apart from Shahbag, other places in Dhaka were unaffected by the movement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At 9:00 p.m., the students ended their agitation and announced a protest march and rally on 12 July to protest the violent police attack on them.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At 5:00 p.m., students gathered at Shahbagh and staged a blockade in the area.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] While students were protesting at Comilla Victoria College, a group of Chhatra League members launched an attack on the protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] During the situation, a student who was recording a video was taken to a hall and beaten by the Chhatra League members.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students protested by blocking the railway tracks in Rajshahi.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In Dhaka, DU students held a press conference in the evening, where they complained that attempts were being made to block the students' movement with lawsuits.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students marched in Dhaka and held a sit-in protest and blockade, later submitting a memorandum to President Mohammed Shahabuddin.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Female students from Rokeya Hall joined the protest by breaking the lock put up by the authorities at the dorm gate.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The government instructed operators to shut down the 4G network in the University of Dhaka area.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At around 11:30 p.m., leaders and members of the Chhatra League attacked protesters at the University of Chittagong injuring 13 protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In Jessore at around 12:00 p.m., students from Jessore University of Science and Technology and Michael Madhusudan College staged a protest, where a member of the Chhatra League attacked and injured a protester.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In Dhaka, Members of the Chhatra League started their procession to Shahbagh from Segunbagicha near Department of Fisheries (Bangladesh) at around 3:45 p.m.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Later in the evening, Chhatra League members attacked students inside Bijoy Ekattor Hall of Dhaka University, where some of the attackers were seen shooting with pistols and carrying sticks.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In response, the protesters also threw brickbats from the inside of the hall to retaliate.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] While covering the protest in the University of Dhaka, two journalists from *The Daily Star* and *Prothom Alo* were assaulted and injured in the attack carried out by the Chhatra League.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At 5:30 p.m., members of the Chhatra League attempted to attack the emergency department of Dhaka Medical College Hospital, where over 200 students injured in the clashes were seeking treatment.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] After several attempts throughout the afternoon, Chhatra League members, some wearing helmets, forcibly entered DMCH around 7:30 p.m. and initiated an attack.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] They targeted students already injured in the quota reform movement and vandalized several ambulances parked at DMCH.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Later the same evening, an attack carried out by the Chhatra League Rajshahi branch at Rajshahi University left six students injured, including the joint convenor of the Bangladesh Students Union at RU.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In Comilla, The Comilla University coordinator of the Students Against Discrimination was assaulted at around 8:00 p.m. when eight Chhatra League members called him to check his phone and beat him.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protesters called for nationwide demonstrations and rallies in all educational institutions of the country at 3:00 p.m. on 16 July.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At around 12:15 a.m., members of the Chhatra League attacked Jahangirnagar University students using firearms.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The students took shelter at the vice-chancellor's residence after breaking its lock.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Around 300 Chhatra League members, armed with galvanized pipes and sticks, threw bricks and glass bottles at the students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Shots were reportedly fired, injuring two journalists, including one from *Dhaka Tribune* and over 50 student protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Police arrived to control the situation, while both groups positioned themselves outside the vice-chancellor's residence.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students claimed the attackers included outsiders, some in their forties.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Later on, the sub-inspector of the Ashulia Police Department instead decided to blame the students by stating that the protesters are to blame for causing "this mayhem".
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] A violent incident involving police and students demanding quota reforms took place in front of Begum Rokeya University, Rangpur between 2:30 p.m. and 3:00 p.m.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Police resorted to lathi charges and firing during the incident.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Abu Sayed, a Begum Rokeya University student and quota reform activist, was shot four times by a police officer.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] He was taken to Rangpur Medical College where the doctors pronounced him dead on arrival.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At around 3:30 p.m., it was reported that in the Farmgate–Khamarbari area, Chhatra League assailants attacked protestors with sticks while students from Government Science College, Dhaka were protesting against the attack of Chatra League in University of Dhaka.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] When the protestors took shelter in the Farmgate metro station, the assailants entered and started to beat the students, which was witnessed by the passengers.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Police were allegedly deployed to control the situation.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] However, DMTCL, the authority responsible for the operation for the Dhaka Metro Rail, denied these claims and stated that guards of the station drove the "miscreants" away as they entered with bamboo sticks.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] They also stated that there was no damage to the station.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] However, they announced plans to close some of the gates of the station complex for some time to prevent the recurrence of such incidents.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] As students at public universities were forcefully vacated, students from various schools, colleges, and private universities joined the cause.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] They protested and blocked roads against the violence of the Chhatra League in the quota reform movement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] During this time, Asif Mahtab Utsha, former lecturer of Brac University, notable for the textbook tearing controversy, joined with his students in front of Jamuna Future Park, being the first teacher in Bangladesh to do so.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] He gave a speech in the open and in front of national media where he rebuked his colleagues for not joining the students and being their shield, while also challenging the Chaatra League criminals who attacked Dhaka University students to come to Bashundhara Gate.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In his speech he attempted to boost morale of the students by saying, "I did not teach my students to fall back.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students of The International University of Scholars, Primeasia University and Fareast International University blocked the Banani area and New Airport road.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students of Notre Dame College protested in the country's main financial hub and the largest central business district of Motijheel at Shapla Square.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students of Daffodil International University also attempted to start a demonstration on the road but instead protested on campus.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students of other universities and colleges also joined the protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Protests also took place in Dhanmondi, specifically in front of the Science Laboratory area and in Uttara.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Gridlocks were also experienced at places like Mohammadpur, Dhanmondi, Mirpur Road, and Gabtoli.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students blocked railway lines in Chittagong and Mohakhali.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The Dhaka–Chittagong, Dhaka–Barisal, Dhaka–Rajshahi and Dhaka–Tangail highways were also blocked.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In the evening, the Ministry of Education announced the indefinite closure of schools and colleges and the postponing of the HSC exam scheduled for 18 July.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The UGC declared that all public and private universities across the country will remain closed until further notice.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At the same time, all affiliated medical, textile, engineering and other colleges will also remain closed.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The commission also directed university authorities to vacate residential halls allegedly considering safety of the students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In remembrance of the fallen, the movement announced a symbolic funeral prayer scheduled for July 17.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Clashes erupted with police after the funeral prayer program organized by the student protesters, the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) and other parties to honor six individuals killed on 16 July for the quota reform movement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The government ordered all students to vacate the residential halls.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protestors rejected the order, to which the authorities deployed police to evacuate the halls.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students who blocked the Dhaka-Barisal highway announced a total shutdown for 18 July, allowing only emergency services, to protest police violence, demand justice for the deceased, and call for a terror-free campus.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Sheikh Hasina addressed the nation at 7:30 p.m., where she announced a judicial probe into the deaths during the anti-quota protests and urged patience until the Supreme Court delivers its verdict, emphasizing justice for the students and condemning the violence.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Students at the university erected the Shaheed Smriti Stambha, a memorial pillar to honor the memory of the dead students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In the morning police clashed with BRAC University students on the streets of Badda.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Police also charged batons and fired tear gas canisters at the students and poisonous tear gas shells at the BRACU campus.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The Mirpur-10 station of the Dhaka Metro was closed for arson at a foot-overbridge beneath it.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Reports indicated that approximately 30 students were killed by the Bangladesh police.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Minister of Law Anisul Haque urged the students to withdraw their movement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The Bangladesh Police, RAB, Bangladesh Bank, Bangladesh Prime Minister's Office and Chhatra League's official website was hacked by a pro-protester group as a response to the violence and attacks carried out by the police and the Chhatra League.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Dhaka Metro Rail services in the capital were suspended, and at around 9 p.m., the government shut down internet access across the entire country.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] A second-year student from the Department of Chemical Engineering and Polymer Science at Shahjalal University of Science and Technology drowned while attempting to cross a canal with friends.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The incident occurred during a police chase amid clashes between students, police and Chhatra League members.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The Dhaka Metropolitan Police, in an attempt to hinder the students' protests, announced the indefinite suspension of public gatherings and processions.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The nationwide shutdown of Internet access begun on 18 July continued into 19 July.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Throughout the country, calls for quota reform protests largely continued.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Around 10:00 a.m., teachers at Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology wore black face coverings in protest.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At approximately 12:45 p.m., after protesters in Kishoreganj District's Bhairab Thana surrounded the police station, police fired into the crowd from within the station, injuring over a hundred students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Some clashes with the police also took place elsewhere, including in Uttara, Mohammadpur, and Badda thanas of Dhaka.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The Mirpur 10 and Kazipara metro stations were vandalised, causing extensive damages worth ৳500 crore (US$41 million).
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In Narsingdi, a group of people stormed a prison and released hundreds of inmates before setting the facility on fire.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The government imposed a curfew at midnight and deployed troops nationwide.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] After the deadly Shutdown, the Students Against Discrimination and the government started negotiations on 19 July night.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At midnight, a meeting took place between three government representatives and three representatives of the protesters: Sarjis Alam, Hasnat Abdullah, Sakib Ahmed Tuhin and Tanvir Ahmed.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Notably, Sarjis Alam was a member of the Chhatra League and participated in the 2019 DUCSU election as a candidate from the Chhatra League.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] During the negotiations, at midnight of 20 July, Nahid Islam, a quota reform movement coordinator, was allegedly taken from a friend's house in Nandipara, according to his father.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] After being released on 21 July, Nahid reported being blindfolded, handcuffed, and tortured before regaining consciousness in Purbachal.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 21 July, the Appellate division of the Supreme Court finally reduced the percentage of quotas from 56% to 7%.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Following the verdict on July 22, the Students Against Discrimination announced a two-day suspension of protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] They demanded that the government lift the curfew, restore internet access, and cease targeting student protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] With the suspension of the protests by the Students Against Discrimination, no further violence was reported by this period.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The agitators later further extended the suspension.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] But mass detentions were continued by the law enforcement agencies.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 26 July, police detained three coordinators of the Students Against Discrimination from the hospital, namely Nahid Islam, Abu Bakar Mazumder and Asif Mahmud.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The Home Minister claimed their detention was for their own security and investigation purposes.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The later day, two more coordinators of the movement– Sarjis Alam and Hasnat Abdullah were detained.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The Additional Deputy Commissioner of the Detective Branch Junaed Alam Sarker and stated that they were detained for interrogation about their alleged connection with the opposition Jamaat-e-Islami and Gono Odhikar Parishad Member-Secretary Nurul Haq Nur.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In response, the movement threatened to resume their protests from 29 July if the three were not released, while also demanding action against ministers and police officers over the deaths of the protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Meanwhile, the government gradually relaxed the curfew restrictions, allowing banks, factories and offices to reopen.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 23 July, the ICT Minister announced that the government would restore broadband internet service partially to banks, business organizations, export sectors, and selected areas after a five-day disruption.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Accordingly, on 24 July, broadband internet services were restored, and on 28 July, mobile internet was restored in Bangladesh, although social media websites like Facebook, Instagram and TikTok continued to be blocked.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 28 July, six protest coordinators of the Students Against Discrimination, who had been taken into custody by the Detective Branch, issued a statement from the DB office announcing the withdrawal of the protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] However, other coordinators of the movement alleged that these individuals had been coerced by the DB into making the statement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The remaining coordinators vowed to continue their protest, with or without the support of the six individuals.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Protesters resumed large-scale demonstrations across various regions of the country after the government ignored an ultimatum to release their leaders.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Police arrested 2,822 students in Dhaka.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] University professors across Bangladesh, under the "Anti-Repression Teachers Rally" banner, have called for an end to student harassment and mass arrests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] They demanded the release of detained students and expressed solidarity with ongoing student protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The rally, held at Dhaka University's Aparajeyo Bangla on July 29, 2024, began with a moment of silence for students killed in the recent quota reform movement, which the teachers labelled the July Massacre.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] A cabinet meeting chaired by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina on 29 July declared that nationwide mourning would be observed on 30 July to honour those killed during the quota reform movement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] While Awami League leaders posted black profile pictures on Facebook, many users in Bangladesh chose red, rejecting the official mourning as a farce and declaring they will mourn only when justice is served for the dead students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 31 July, the Students Against Discrimination organized a nationwide protest named **"March for Justice"** in response to the series of killings, mass arrests, attacks, lawsuits, enforced disappearances, and murders of students and citizens.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Abdul Hannan Masud, one of the coordinators of the movement, confirmed the event.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protest was scheduled to take place at 12 pm across court premises, campuses, and streets nationwide, advocating for nine specific demands of the students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The movement sought the support and cooperation of teachers, lawyers, human rights activists, professionals, workers, and citizens.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At 11:20, students from Shahjalal University of Science and Technology (SUST) and other educational institutions in Sylhet marched from the university gate towards Court Point in support of the protest.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] By 11:00, protesters began assembling at the Chittagong Court premises.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Despite police barricades, around 200 protesters entered the premises and staged a sit-in.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] A group of 50 to 60 pro-BNP lawyers stood in solidarity with the students, while pro-Awami League lawyers conducted a counter-march.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protest in Chittagong concluded around 15:15 with a march from the court premises to the New Market intersection.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Around 13:15, students from BUET, the University of Dhaka, and several other universities marched towards the High Court.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Their progress was halted by the police near the Bangladesh Shishu Academy, resulting in the detention of several students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In response, the students gathered at Doel Square, later joined by teachers from Dhaka University's White Panel.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protest in Dhaka ended around 15:00 after nearly three hours of demonstration.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] From 12:20 to 13:00, University of Rajshahi students blocked the Dhaka-Rajshahi Highway as part of the protest.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Police detained five students from the university during the demonstration.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At 15:00, after being shut down for 13 days, Facebook, WhatsApp and other social media platforms were reopened.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In memory of those killed, injured, and tortured by police during the 2024 quota reform movement, the Students Against Discrimination announced a nationwide program titled **"Remembering the Heroes"** on 1 August.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] This announcement was made in a press release signed by Rifat Rashid, one of the co-coordinators of the Students Against Discrimination, on 31 July.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Additionally, he called for online and offline campaigns in support of the movement and memory of the martyrs, using the hashtags *JulyMassacre* and *RememberingOurHeroes* on social media platforms.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At 12:30 p.m., teachers and students of Jahangirnagar University held a protest song rally and cultural gathering to protest the attacks on Dhaka University teachers, the mass arrests of protesting students and citizens, and the harassment through false cases.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In solidarity with the movement, twelve teachers from the Daffodil International University also participated in the JU event.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] After the 24-hour ultimatum for the unconditional release of the six coordinators of the quota reform movement expired, several prominent citizens, including Iftekharuzzaman, Rizwana Hasan, and Asif Nazrul, announced that they would go to the DB office on the afternoon of 1 August.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The government banned the Bangladesh Jamaat-e-Islami, its student wing, the Bangladesh Islami Chhatra Shibir and its associated bodies citing anti-terrorism laws following their involvement in the protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] So far, 274 cases have been filed against students in various police stations in Dhaka Metropolitan.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In these cases, up to the morning of 1 August, 3,011 students have been arrested by the Dhaka Metropolitan Police.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The police released six student leaders as the government looked to calm tensions and forestall fresh demonstrations.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Upon being released from the DB office, several coordinators announced that they would continue the movement and shared their statements on social media.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In Narayanganj, the Candlelight Vigil program organized in support of "Remembering the Heroes" was disrupted by police intervention.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] During this time, the police baton-charged the students, injuring at least ten.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The protesters sought justice for victims affected by the unrest and police crackdown following the release of student leaders.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] This release did not alleviate public anger, leading to renewed protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Demonstrators demanded the reopening of schools and universities across the country and, called for Sheikh Hasina's resignation.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Clashes occurred as police fired rubber bullets, tear gas shells, and sound grenades in several locations, including Uttara, Khulna, Sylhet, and Habiganj.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] One police officer was beaten to death by protesters in Khulna, while one civilian died in Habiganj.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Due to the renewed unrest, internet service providers again restricted access to Facebook, WhatsApp, and Telegram.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] After five hours of restriction, access to Facebook and Messenger were reopened; however Telegram remained restricted.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On the same day, the six coordinators, previously detained by the Detective Branch, said they were coerced into withdrawing from the movement, alleging that the statement was obtained under duress for national broadcast.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Following the ongoing violence and sabotage incidents centered around the quota reform movement, 78 HSC candidates arrested in related cases were granted bail from various courts nationwide.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Among them, 55 were from the Dhaka Division, 14 from the Chittagong Division, six from the Khulna Division, and three from the Rangpur Division.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] UNICEF expressed concern over the deaths of at least 32 children during the protest crackdown.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Sanjay Wijesekera, UNICEF Regional Director for South Asia, urged swift measures to ensure the children can return to school.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In the early hours of the day, an injured person died while receiving treatment.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] He added that they had endured torture while in police custody and had resorted to a hunger strike while detained by police and the Detective Branch.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Around 10:30 a.m., students from various educational institutions in Rajshahi marched and gathered in front of the Rajshahi University of Engineering and Technology (RUET), chanting slogans.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The students took to the streets demanding the resignation of Sheikh Hasina.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The court granted bail to Arif Sohel, a coordinator of the Students Against Discrimination, who remained in jail despite the decision.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In Chittagong, there was an attack on the residence of Education Minister Mohibul Hasan Chowdhury.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] During this incident, two cars parked in front of the house were vandalized, and one of them was set on fire.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Earlier, around 5:30 p.m., there was also an attack on the office of Md Mohiuddin Bacchu, the Member of Parliament for Chittagong-10, located in the Lalkhan Bazar.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The office was set on fire during the attack.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In another incident in Sreepur, Gazipur one person was killed during clashes between police and protesting students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In Rangpur, two police officers were temporarily suspended in connection with the death of Abu Sayed on 16 July.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The two officers are ASI Amir Hossain of Rangpur Police Lines and Constable Sujan Chandra Roy of Tajhat Police Station.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] During an Student Against Discrimination movement in Sylhet, clashes occurred between the police and the students along with the public.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Initial reports indicated that over a hundred people were injured in the conflict.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At around 1:30 p.m. in Race Course, Comilla, leaders and activists of the Chhatra League, Jubo League, and Swechchhasebak League attacked a mass rally of Students Against Discrimination protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] During the attack, they fired openly at the students, resulting in 10 students being shot and a total of 30 people being injured.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In Bogra, there were repeated clashes between protesting students and the police.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] From 4 p.m. to around 6 p.m., these confrontations lasted nearly two hours.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] During the conflict, the police fired tear gas shells, sound grenades, rubber bullets, and shotgun rounds.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Several areas of the city, including Satmatha, Circuit House Mor, Romena Afaz Road, Kalibari Mor, Bir Muktijoddha Rezaul Baki Road, and Jailkhana Mor, turned into battlegrounds.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] At least six students were shot, and an additional 50 students were injured.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On this day the movement ended and was succeeded by the Non-cooperation movement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Following the overthrow of the Awami League, the Revolutionary Workers Party of Bangladesh organised a student assembly to meet with the interim government and consult on the policies of said government, meeting with parties like the BNP.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The massacre was the violent suppression and mass killings in Bangladesh during the July Revolution from 16 July to 5 August 2024.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] It is triggered by the reinstatement of a controversial quota system and widespread public dissatisfaction, the crackdown was carried out by the government led by the Awami League, its affiliated groups such as the Chhatra League, and various law-enforcement agencies.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] With the deterioration of the law and order situation in the country, Minister of Law Anisul Haque conferred with the Attorney General AM Amin Uddin about appealing to the court for a hearing of the case on July 21.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On the same day, the Appellate Division of Supreme Court ordered an overhaul of the quota reservation system.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] It ordered 93% of recruitment in government jobs to be based on merit and 5% to be reserved for the children of freedom fighters, martyred freedom fighters and *Biranganas*, 1% for the ethnic minorities and 1% for the third gender and the disabled people with immediate effect.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Accordingly, on 23 July, the Ministry of Public Administration published a gazette notification in line with the Supreme Court verdict.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] In the post-gazette news conference, Anisul Huq said the new quota system will be followed while recruiting employees directly in all government, semi-government, autonomous and semi-autonomous institutions, statutory bodies and different corporations.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Despite the ruling, student protesters pledged to continue demonstrating for other demands such as the release of people imprisoned during the protests and the resignations of officials deemed responsible for the violence that occurred with it.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] However, in the afternoon, central coordinator Nahid Islam announced that they had no plans to negotiate with the government.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The mass killings carried out by the law enforcement agencies were described as "July massacre" in various sources.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The report stated that restrictions on communication and state interference in hospitals make this figure an undercount.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] According to UNICEF, at least 32 children died during the protest crackdown surrounding the protests and unrest in July.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] *Prothom Alo* found that out of the 354 people killed it had counted during the protests, 39 were children.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Six people were reported killed on 17 July: Md.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Shahjahan, a 25-year-old hawker from the New Market area; Md.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Farooq, a 32-year-old employee of a furniture shop; Md.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Wasim Akram, a 22-year-old student of the Sociology Department at Chittagong College and an activist of Chatra Dal; Faisal Ahmed Shanto, a 24-year-old student of Omargani M.E.S.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] College; Sabuj Ali, a 25-year-old member of the Chhatra League and a student of Dhaka College; and most notably, Abu Sayed, a 25-year-old student of the Department of English at Begum Rokeya University.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Another four were killed in a clash between the police at Uttara, including two students of Northern University, while one was killed in Narsingdi in a clash between police and students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The movement resulted in huge damage of various state properties in Bangladesh.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] According to a report by Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha, at least thirty major state establishments experienced arson and severe damage.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The state broadcaster, Bangladesh Television (BTV), was attacked and set on fire on 18 July 2024.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The building suffered extensive damage, with several sections completely burnt.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Sheikh Hasina visited the site and expressed deep sorrow over the incident.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] A major data center in Dhaka was set on fire, causing severe disruptions to internet and telecom services across the country and the loss of 70–80% of the country's bandwidth.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Arsons also occurred in the toll stations of Dhaka Elevated Expressway and Mayor Mohammed Hanif Flyover, and two Dhaka Metro stations, including the Mirpur-10 station.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Footage of Sheikh Hasina visiting the station and shedding tears on 25 July was criticised on social media, with users accusing her of failing to react similarly to the loss of life during the protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] According to Bangladesh Police, 235 police infrastructures and 281 vehicles were vandalized and set on fire.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 19 July, a violent attack on Narsingdi District Jail resulted in a massive jailbreak.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Armed assailants, allegedly linked to Jamaat-e-Islami and BNP by the government, stormed the prison, set fires, and broke open cell locks, allowing 826 prisoners, including nine militants, to escape.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The attackers looted weapons, ammunition, and food supplies while causing extensive damage to the facility.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Several prison guards were killed during the attack, and the attackers fled with the escaped prisoners.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Bangladesh's economy suffered losses of over $1.2 billion as a result of the nationwide curfew and protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Among the industries greatly affected were ready-made garments, steelmaking, pharmaceuticals, ceramics and outsourcing and e-commerce.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The Bangladesh Police including Detective Branch (DB) and RAB arrested a large number of student protesters and members of opposition political parties.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] As of July 30, the total count reached over 9600.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 23 July, plainclothes police arrest a non-protester HSC examinee after failing to find his elder brother.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 26 July, plainclothes police officers detained three protest coordinators, namely Nahid Islam, Asif Mahmud and Abu Baker Majumder from Gonoshasthaya Kendra hospital.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The three were receiving medical treatment for injuries they received from alleged beatings and torture while in prior police custody.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 27 July, DB detained protest coordinators Sarjis Alam and Hasnat Abdullah.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On July 28, plainclothes police detained two more protest coordinators, namely Nusrat Tabassum and Arif Shohel.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] These detained coordinators but Arif Shohel are the one who issued a statement from the DB office announcing the withdrawal of the protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] However, other coordinators of the Students Against Discrimination alleged that these individuals had been coerced by the DB into making the statement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The remaining coordinators announced to continue their protest.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] After missing for days Arif Shohel and Asif Mahtab Utsha, a former teacher of BRAC University placed six-day remand each.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On July 29, police arrested at least 34 protesters including coordinators.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On July 20, Nurul Haq Nur, associated with the 2018 Bangladesh quota reform movement, was arrested by police on charges of involvement in the 18 July arson attack on Setu Bhaban, although there were claims he was not involved.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Some observers viewed the arrest as politically motivated.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Bangladeshi law mandates that an arrested person must be presented in court within 24 hours; failure to do so is considered an enforced disappearance.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] According to Nur's wife, he was unaccounted for 40 hours before being brought to court, raising questions about the legality of his detention.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] She also alleged that Nur was tortured by law enforcers while in remand.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On 27 July, Hasanatul Islam Faiyaz, a 17-year-old, was presented in a lower court in Dhaka and placed on a seven-day remand.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] He was the 16th of 17 individuals charged in connection with the killing of a police officer near Matuail Hospital during the protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] The charges included murder, concealment of the body, and theft of the officer's motorcycle.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] Although the case file listed Faiyaz's age as 19, his birth certificate confirmed he was 17, born on 19 April 2007.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p01] On July 28, the Chief Metropolitan Magistrate Court Judge Tahmina Haque canceled the remand order following an appeal, citing the incorrect age in the case file which violates UNCRC and the "Children's Act, 2013".
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Razakars were a Bengali paramilitary force during the Bangladesh Liberation War which collaborated with the Pakistani forces to halt the independence of Bangladesh.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] In modern-day Bangladesh, the term *razakar* is used as a pejorative, meaning "traitor" or "collaborator", similar to the usage of "Quisling" in the Western World.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Using the term razakar can be highly insulting in Bangladesh.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] In response to Sheikh Hasina's comment, in the early hours of 15 July, students began using new slogans out of anger such as "তুমি কে, আমি কে? রাজাকার, রাজাকার! কে বলেছে, কে বলেছে? স্বৈরাচার, স্বৈরাচার!" (lit.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] The Autocrat, the Autocrat!'), "এক, দুই, তিন, চার, আমরা হলাম রাজাকার" (lit.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] 'One, two, three, four, we are all Rajakars'), and "চাইতে গেলাম অধিকার, হয়ে গেলাম রাজাকার!" (lit.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] 'Sought for rights, got turned into a Razakar!') protesters argued that the Prime Minister's statement indirectly labelled them as "Razakars" and demeaned them for advocating for quota reform, which led them to adopt the slogan.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] The Bangladesh Chhatra League, the student wing of the ruling party Awami League, threatened that any protester using these slogans would face consequences, as they viewed these actions as something offensive to the spirit of the liberation war and freedom fighters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] It also announced plans to take action if the usage of these slogans continued.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] In light of these events, Sheikh Hasina questioned the education of the protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Bangladesh Armed Forces used United Nations marked vehicles including APCs during a curfew imposed by the government.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] As of 1 August 2024, the United Nations continues to engage with the Bangladesh Army for its peacekeeping missions, with Bangladesh contributing the third-largest number of troops globally, totalling 5,614 personnel.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] This engagement persists despite ongoing concerns and reports regarding the country's governance practices.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] On 24 June, Foreign Minister Hasan Mahmud told reporters that some vehicles were "rented to the UN peace mission" and the authorities had forgotten to remove the logos.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] It is speculated that Bangladesh and its military may face potential sanctions from the Western countries and scrutiny from the International Criminal Court for deploying UN-marked vehicles to target unarmed protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Bangladesh's largest opposition party, the Bangladesh Nationalist Party, denounced the Chhatra League attacks on the protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Thirty eminent citizens of the country condemned the loss of lives in violent clashes during the protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Non-governmental organization Transparency International Bangladesh also denounced the suppressions.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] In an interview published on 14 August, nine days after the resignation of Sheikh Hasina, her son and the former IT advisor Sajeeb Wazed expressed that the stand of the fifth Hasina ministry on the quota system was wrong and they should have supported the protesters from the first.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Muhammad Zafar Iqbal, a renowned Bangladeshi author and former professor at Shahjalal University of Science and Technology, remarked that he would not like to visit Dhaka University again, claiming he would see the "Razakars" in the students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] This statement sparked immense outrage and controversy among the supporters and the participants in the quota reform movement.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Many online bookshops, including Rokomari.com, announced they would no longer sell or promote his literary works, removing his books from their websites.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Similarly, students of the university declared him a *persona non grata*.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Human Rights Watch urged the Bangladeshi government to "end the crisis, punish those committing serious crimes, and protect" protesting students.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] They also called for increased scrutiny of Bangladeshi security forces by the UK and the EU.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] UNICEF expressed concerns over the death of 32 children in the protests.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Sanjay Wijesekera, UNICEF Regional Director for South Asia, urged swift measures to ensure that children can return to school.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] The All India Students Association denounced the violence and expressed their solidarity with student protesters.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] The Awami Ittehad Party also condemned the violence and urged safety for the Indian nationals residing there.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Amnesty International condemned the attacks against protesters and called on the government "to immediately guarantee the safety of all peaceful protesters and proper treatment of all those injured".
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Ma Thida, Chair of PEN International's Writers in Prison Committee, condemned the violence and called on the Bangladesh government to protect journalists and ensure their freedom of expression.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] International Federation for Human Rights and Odhikar urged the government to investigate the law enforcement crackdown and hold officers accountable for unnecessary or disproportionate force.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] They also called for an immediate, independent investigation into attacks on protesters by BCL members.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] Célia Mercier, Head of Reporters Without Borders's South Asia Desk, demanded that those responsible for the violent attacks on journalists be identified and brought to justice immediately.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] She also called on authorities to guarantee the safety of journalists and the right to information.
[src:asia/2024-bangladesh-quota-reform-movement-p02] The digital civil rights NGO Access Now urged the government for unrestricted internet access and transparency during disruptions, with service providers giving prior notification and explanations to users.
[src:asia/3g-countries] Prepared in February 2011, a Citigroup report prepared by analysts Willem Buiter (Chief Economist) and Ebrahim Rahbari claimed that BRICS (Brazil, Russia, India, and China, plus South Africa) countries have "outlived their usefulness".
[src:asia/3g-countries] "We hold the view that categories emerging markets, advanced economies, developing countries, BRICS, Next Eleven or the Growth Markets are all labels belonging to classification schemes that either have outlived their usefulness or are unlikely to ever have any," the two analysts said.
[src:asia/3g-countries] So, long run continues growths are important, although some of the eleven countries identified are poor today and have decades of catch-up growth to look forward to.
[src:asia/3g-countries] Note: China and India highlighted in gold with **bold** text as also BRIC countries.
[src:asia/3g-countries] GDP per capita measured at 2018 PPP USD.
[src:asia/3g-countries] Average growth is average growth in forecast of real GDP per capita measured at 2018 PPP USD.
[src:asia/3g-countries] The most promising growth prospects countries are Vietnam, Bangladesh, China, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Iraq, Mongolia, Nigeria, Philippines, and Sri Lanka.
[src:asia/3g-countries] China and India as BRIC countries are 3G countries, but not for Brazil and Russia.
[src:asia/3g-countries] Developing Asia and Africa will be fastest growing regions until 2050, driven by population and income growth, so all 3G countries came from two continents (Asia with nine countries and Africa with two) and none came from the other continents.
[src:asia/3g-countries] Vietnam has the highest Global Growth Generators Index among the 11 major economies, and China is second with 0.81, followed by India's 0.71.
[src:asia/3g-countries] This holds Vietnam as the world's highest potential source of high growth and profitable investment opportunities.
[src:asia/3g-countries] As of October 2011, based on a report from the HSBC Trade Confidence Index (TCI) and HSBC Trade Forecast there are four countries with significant trade volume growth, i.e.
[src:asia/3g-countries] Egypt, India, Vietnam and Indonesia with growth expected at least 7.3 percent per year until 2025.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] Ciechanover was born in Haifa, Israel on 1 October 1947 into a Jewish family.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] He is the son of Bluma (Lubashevsky), a teacher of English, and Yitzhak Ciechanover, an office worker in a law firm.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] His parents immigrated to Israel from Poland in the 1920s.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] Upon graduating from high school, Ciechanover joined the Academic Reserve (*Atuda*) and studied medicine at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] He earned a master's degree in science in 1971 and graduated from Hadassah Medical School in Jerusalem in 1974.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] He received his doctorate in biochemistry in 1981 from the Technion – Israel Institute of Technology in Haifa before conducting postdoctoral research in the laboratory of Harvey Lodish at the Whitehead Institute at MIT from 1981 to 1984.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] Ciechanover is currently a Technion Distinguished Research Professor in the Ruth and Bruce Rappaport Faculty of Medicine and Research Institute at the Technion.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] He is a member of the Israel Academy of Sciences and Humanities, the Pontifical Academy of Sciences, the National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine, the Russian Academy of Sciences and is a foreign associate of the United States National Academy of Sciences.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] In 2008, he was a visiting Distinguished Chair Professor at NCKU, Taiwan.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] As part of Shenzhen's 13th Five-Year Plan funding research in emerging technologies and opening "Nobel laureate research labs", in 2018 he opened the Ciechanover Institute of Precision and Regenerative Medicine at the Chinese University of Hong Kong, Shenzhen campus.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] Ciechanover is one of Israel's first Nobel Laureates in science, earning his Nobel Prize in 2004 for his work in ubiquitination.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] He is honored for playing a central role in the history of Israel and in the history of the Technion – Israel Institute of Technology.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] Ciechanover has served on the scientific advisory boards of the following companies: Rosetta Genomics (Chairman), BioLineRx, Ltd, StemRad, Ltd, Allosterix Ltd, Proteologics, Inc, MultiGene Vascular Systems, Ltd, Protalix BioTherapeutics, BioTheryX, Inc., and Haplogen, GmbH.
[src:asia/aaron-ciechanover] Ciechanover is a member of the advisory board of Patient Innovation, a nonprofit, international, multilingual, free venue for patients and caregivers of any disease to share their innovations.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam was scientific advisor to the Ministry of Science and Technology in Pakistan from 1960 to 1974, a position from which he played a major and influential role in the development of the country's science infrastructure.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam contributed to numerous developments in theoretical and particle physics in Pakistan.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] He was the founding director of the Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission (SUPARCO), and responsible for the establishment of the Theoretical Physics Group (TPG).
[src:asia/abdus-salam] For this, he is viewed as the "scientific father" of this program.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1974, Abdus Salam departed from his country in protest after the Parliament of Pakistan unanimously passed a parliamentary bill declaring members of the Ahmadiyya Muslim community, to which Salam belonged, non-Muslim.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam's notable achievements include the Pati–Salam model, a Grand Unified Theory he proposed along with Jogesh Pati in 1974, magnetic photon, vector meson, work on supersymmetry and most importantly, electroweak theory, for which he was awarded the Nobel Prize.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam made a major contribution in quantum field theory and in the advancement of Mathematics at Imperial College London.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] With his student, Riazuddin, Salam made important contributions to the modern theory on neutrinos, neutron stars and black holes, as well as the work on modernising quantum mechanics and quantum field theory.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] As a teacher and science promoter, Salam is remembered as a founder and scientific father of mathematical and theoretical physics in Pakistan during his term as the chief scientific advisor to the president.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam heavily contributed to the rise of Pakistani physics within the global physics community.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Up until shortly before his death, Salam continued to contribute to physics, and to advocate for the development of science in third-world countries.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Abdus Salam was born on 29 January 1926 in Jhang in the Punjab Province of British India (present day in Pakistan) into a Punjabi family professing Ahmadiyya.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] He belonged to the Muslim Rajput community, his son Ahmad Salam later recounted that he would tell him stories of Rajput cultural history "of which he was very proud".
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Jagjit Singh, in his biography of Salam, says that his family traditionally traced its genealogy back to a Rajput prince named Buddahn who converted to Islam at the hands of a Sufi preacher and later founded the city of Jhang around the year 1160.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam was the son of Chaudhary Muhammad Hussain, a school teacher of Jhang and Hajirah who belonged to Faizullah Chak near Batala.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] The name Choudhary Muhammad Hussain gave his son was Abd al-Salam which means "Servant of God".
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Abd means servant and Salam is one of the 99 names of God in the Qur'an.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In English, his name is usually transliterated as Abdus Salam, which should be understood as a single given name.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] His father followed the custom of not giving a surname.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Later in his life he added Mohammad to his name.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam established an early reputation in Punjab for outstanding academic performance.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] At age 14, he scored the highest marks ever recorded for the entrance examination of the Punjab University, earning a full scholarship to the Government College of Lahore.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Instead of moving to Lahore immediately, he remained in Jhang and studied for two years at Government Intermediate College.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1942, he passed his FA examinations with the highest scores in the province.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1942, Salam moved to Lahore to study at Government College.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] As a fourth-year student, he published an elegant solution for a mathematical problem originally studied by Srinivasa Ramanujan.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1944, his mathematics exam results set a new Punjab record.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam also excelled in Urdu and English literature, which could have led him to pursue further studies in English.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] However, on the recommendation of a mentor, he chose to continue with an M.A. in mathematics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] At his father's urging, Salam attempted to enter the Indian Civil Service (ICS), considered the most prestigious career path for young graduates.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] He applied to the Indian Railways but was rejected after failing the medical optical tests; examiners also ruled that he was too young to qualify.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam remained in Lahore, completing his M.A. in mathematics at Government College in 1946 with record marks.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] That same year, he was awarded a scholarship to St John's College, Cambridge, where he enrolled in the undergraduate Mathematical Tripos and graduated in 1949 with a Double First-Class Honours in Mathematics and Physics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Although his M.A. from Lahore would have qualified him to proceed directly to research, he still intended at that stage to pursue the ICS, and was advised to obtain a Cambridge mathematics degree first.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1950, he received the Smith's Prize from Cambridge University for the most outstanding pre-doctoral contribution to Physics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] After finishing his degrees, Fred Hoyle advised Salam to spend another year in the Cavendish Laboratory to do research in experimental physics, but Salam had no patience for carrying out long experiments in the laboratory.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam returned to Jhang and renewed his scholarship and returned to the United Kingdom to do his doctorate.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] While at Cavendish, Salam entered a Ph.D program.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] His doctoral thesis titled "Developments in quantum theory of fields" contained comprehensive and fundamental work in quantum electrodynamics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] By the time it was published in 1951, it had already gained him an international reputation and the Adams Prize.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] During his doctoral studies, his mentors challenged him to solve within one year an intractable problem which had defied such great minds as Paul Dirac and Richard Feynman.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Within six months, Salam had found a solution for the renormalization of meson theory.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] As he proposed the solution at the Cavendish Laboratory, Salam had attracted the attention of Hans Bethe, J.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] After receiving his doctorate in 1951, Salam returned to Lahore at the Government College University as a professor of mathematics, where he remained till 1954.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1952, he was appointed professor and chair of the Department of Mathematics at the neighbouring University of the Punjab.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In the latter capacity, Salam sought to update the university curriculum, introducing a course in quantum mechanics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] He began to supervise the education of students who were particularly influenced by him.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] As a result, Riazuddin remained the only student of Salam who had the privilege to study under Salam at the undergraduate and post-graduate level in Lahore, and post-doctoral level in Cambridge University.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1953, Salam was unable to establish a research institute in Lahore, as he faced strong opposition from his peers.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam went back to Cambridge and joined St John's College.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] During 1957, his tenure at Imperial College, London started.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] As time passed, this department became one of the prestigious research departments that included well known physicists such as Steven Weinberg, Tom Kibble, Gerald Guralnik, C.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] At Cambridge and Imperial College he formed a group of theoretical physicists, the majority of whom were his Pakistani students.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] At age 33, Salam became one of the youngest persons to be elected a Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS) in 1959.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam took a fellowship at Princeton University in 1959, where he met with J.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Robert Oppenheimer and to whom he presented his research work on neutrinos.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Oppenheimer and Salam discussed the foundation of electrodynamics, problems and their solution.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] His dedicated personal assistant was Jean Bouckley.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1980, Salam became a foreign fellow of the Bangladesh Academy of Sciences.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam made an important and significant contribution in Particle physics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In his early career in Pakistan, Salam was greatly interested in mathematical series and their relation to physics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam had played an influential role in the advancement of nuclear physics, but he maintained and dedicated himself to mathematics and theoretical physics and focused Pakistan to do more research in theoretical physics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] However, he regarded nuclear physics (nuclear fission and nuclear power) as a non-pioneering part of physics as it had already "happened".
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Even in Pakistan, Salam was the leading driving force in theoretical physics, with many scientists he continued to influence and encourage to keep their work on theoretical physics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam had a prolific research career in theoretical and high-energy physics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam had worked on the neutrino with his chiral symmetry.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam later passed his work to Riazuddin, who made pioneering contributions in neutrinos.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam introduced the massive Higgs bosons to the theory of the Standard Model, where he later predicted the existence of proton decay.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1962, Salam published his theoretical work on the vector meson.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1961, Salam began to work with John Clive Ward on symmetries and electroweak unification.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1964, Salam and Ward worked on a Gauge theory for the weak and electromagnetic interaction, subsequently obtaining SU(2) × U(1) model.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam was convinced that all the elementary particle interactions are actually the gauge interactions.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1968, together with Weinberg and Sheldon Glashow, Salam formulated the mathematical concept of their work.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] While in Imperial College, Salam, along with Glashow and Jeffrey Goldstone, mathematically proved the Goldstone's theorem, that a massless spin-zero object must appear in a theory as a result of spontaneous breaking of a continuous global symmetry.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1967-8, Salam and Weinberg incorporated the Higgs mechanism into Glashow's discovery, giving it a modern form in electroweak theory, and thus theorised half of the Standard Model.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1968, together with Weinberg and Sheldon Glashow, Salam finally formulated the mathematical concept of their work.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1966, Salam carried out pioneering work on a hypothetical particle.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam showed the possible electromagnetic interaction between the Magnetic monopole and the C-violation, thus he formulated the magnetic photon.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Following the publication of PRL Symmetry Breaking papers in 1964, Steven Weinberg and Salam were the first to apply the Higgs mechanism to electroweak symmetry breaking.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam provided a mathematical postulation for the interaction between the Higgs boson and the electroweak symmetry theory.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1972, Salam began to work with Indian-American theoretical physicist Jogesh Pati.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Pati wrote to Salam several times expressing interest to work under Salam's direction, in response to which Salam eventually invited Pati to the ICTP seminar in Pakistan.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam suggested to Pati that there should be some deep reason why the protons and electrons are so different and yet carry equal but opposite electric charge.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Protons are composed of quarks, but the electroweak theory was concerned only with the electrons and neutrinos, with nothing postulated about quarks.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] If all of nature's ingredients could be brought together in one new symmetry, it might reveal a reason for the various features of these particles and the forces they feel.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] This led to the development of Pati–Salam model in particle physics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam had worked on forces from 1959 with Glashow and Weinberg.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Glashow had also formulated the same work, and the theory was combined in 1966.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1967, Salam proved the electroweak unification theory mathematically, and finally published the papers.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] For this achievement, Salam, Glashow, and Weinberg were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1979.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] The Nobel Prize Foundation paid tribute to the scientists and issued a statement saying: "For their contributions to the theory of the unified weak and electromagnetic interaction between elementary particles, including, inter alia, the prediction of the weak neutral current".
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Only one known official replica of the Nobel Prize Medal was ever produced by the Mint of Pakistan in 1979/80.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] This medal has a large test cut and damage from two to three o'clock.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] The replica medal was sold at auction to an unknown bidder on April 23, 2025.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In the 1970s Salam continued trying to unify forces by including the strong interaction in a Grand Unified Theory.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1961 he approached President Khan to set up the country's first national space agency, thus on 16 September 1961 the Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission was established, with Salam as its first director.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Before 1960, very little work on scientific development was done, and scientific activities in Pakistan were almost diminished.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam called Ishfaq Ahmad, a nuclear physicist, who had left for Switzerland where he joined CERN, back to Pakistan.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] With the support of Salam, PAEC established PAEC Lahore Center-6, with Ishfaq Ahmad as its first director.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1967, Salam became a central and administrative figure to lead the research in Theoretical and Particle physics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] With the establishment of the Institute of Physics at Quaid-e-Azam University, research in theoretical and particle physics was engaged.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Under Salam's direction, physicists tackled the greatest outstanding problems in physics and mathematics and their physics research reached a point that prompted worldwide recognition of Pakistani physicists.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] From the 1950s, Salam had tried establishing high-powered research institutes in Pakistan, though he was unable to do so.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] He moved PAEC Headquarters to a bigger building, and established research laboratories all over the country.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] On the direction of Salam, Ishrat Hussain Usmani set up plutonium and uranium exploration committees throughout the country.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In October 1961, Salam travelled to the United States and signed a space co-operation agreement between Pakistan and US.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In November 1961, the US National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) started to build a space facility – Flight Test Center (FTC) – at Sonmiani, a coastal town in Balochistan Province.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam served as its first technical director.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] While in the IAEA, Salam had consulted about the establishment of the International Centre for Theoretical Physics (ICTP), a research physics institution, in Trieste, Italy...
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam obtained permission from President Ayub Khan to set up the Karachi Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Also in 1965, led by Salam, the United States and Pakistan signed an agreement in which the US provided Pakistan with a small research reactor (PARR-I).
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam had a long-held dream to establish a research institute in Pakistan, which he had advocated for on many occasions.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1965 again, Salam and architect Edward Durell Stone signed a contract for the establishment of the Pakistan Institute of Nuclear Science and Technology (PINSTECH) at Nilore, Islamabad.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In early 1961, Salam approached President Khan to lay the foundations of Pakistan's first executive agency to co-ordinate space research.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] By executive order on 16 September 1961 the Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission (SUPARCO) was established with Salam founding director.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam knew the importance of nuclear technology in Pakistan, for civilian and peaceful purposes.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] But, according to his biographers, Salam played an ambiguous role in Pakistan's own atomic bomb project.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] As late as the 1960s, Salam made an unsuccessful proposal for the establishment of a nuclear fuel reprocessing plant, but it was deferred on economic grounds by Ayub Khan.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] According to Rehman, Salam's influence in nuclear development was diminished as late as 1974, and he became critical of Bhutto's control over science.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] But Salam personally did not terminate his connection with the scientists working in the theoretical physics division at PAEC.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] As early as 1972–73, he had been a great advocate for the atomic bomb project, but subsequently took a stance against it after he fell out with Bhutto over the Second Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan which declared the Ahmaddiya denomination to be non-Islamic.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1965, Salam led the establishing of the nuclear research institute – PINSTECH.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1965, the plutonium Pakistan Atomic Research Reactor (PARR-I) went critical under Salams' leadership.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1973, Salam proposed the idea of establishing an annual college to promote scientific activities in the country to the chairman of PAEC, Munir Khan, who accepted and fully supported the idea.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] This led to the establishment of the International Nathiagali Summer College on Physics and Contemporary Needs (INSC), where each year since 1976 scientists from all over the world come to Pakistan to interact with local scientists.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] The first annual INSC conference was held on advanced particle and nuclear physics.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In November 1971, Salam met with Zulfikar Ali Bhutto in his residence, and following Bhutto's advice, went to the United States to avoid the Indo-Pakistani War of 1971.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam travelled to the US and returned to Pakistan with scientific literature about the Manhattan Project, and calculations involving atomic bombs.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1972, the Government of Pakistan learned about the development status of the first atomic bomb completed under the Indian nuclear programme.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] On 20 January 1972, Salam, as Science Advisor to the president of Pakistan, managed and participated in a secret meeting of nuclear scientists with former prime minister, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in Multan, known as the 'Multan Meeting'.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] At this meeting Bhutto orchestrated the development of a deterrence programme.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Usmani protested, believing that the country had neither the facilities or talent to carry out such an ambitious and technologically demanding project, whilst Salam remained quiet.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Here, Bhutto entrusted Salam and appointed Munir Khan as Chairman of PAEC, and head of the atomic bomb program, as Salam had supported Khan.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] A few months after the meeting, Salam, Khan, and Riazuddin, met with Bhutto in his residence where the scientists briefed him about the nuclear weapons program.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] After the meeting, Salam established the 'Theoretical Physics Group' (TPG) in PAEC.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam led groundbreaking work at TPG until 1974.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] An office was set up for Salam in the Prime Ministers' Secretariat by order of Bhutto.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam immediately started to motivate and invite scientists to begin work with PAEC in the development of fission weapons.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In December 1972, two theoretical physicists working at the International Centre for Theoretical Physics were asked by Salam to report to Munir Ahmad Khan, the scientific director of the program.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] This marked the beginning of the TPG, reporting directly to Salam.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] The TPG, in PAEC, was assigned to conduct research in fast neutron calculations, hydrodynamics (how the explosion produced by a chain reaction might behave), problems of neutron diffusion, and the development of theoretical designs of Pakistan's nuclear weapon devices.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Later, the TPG under Riazuddin began to directly report to Salam, and the work on the theoretical design of the nuclear weapon was completed in 1977.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1972, Salam formed the Mathematical Physics Group, under Raziuddin Siddiqui, that was charged, with TPG, with carrying out research in the theory of simultaneity during the detonation process, and the mathematics involved in the theory of nuclear fission.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Following India's surprise nuclear test – Pokhran-I – in 1974, Munir Ahmad Khan had called a meeting to initiate work on an atomic bomb.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam was there and Muhammad Hafeez Qureshi was appointed head of the Directorate of Technical Development (DTD) in PAEC.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] The DTD was set up to co-ordinate the work of the various specialised groups of scientists and engineers working on different aspects of the atomic bomb.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] The word "bomb" was never used in this meeting, but the participants fully understood what was being discussed.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In March 1974, Salam and Khan also established the Wah Group Scientist that was charged with manufacturing materials, explosive lenses and triggering mechanism development of the weapon.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Following the setting up of DTD, Salam, Riazuddin and Munir Ahmad Khan, visited the Pakistan Ordnance Factories (POF) where they held talks with senior military engineers led by POF chairman Lieutenant-General Qamar Ali Mirza.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] It was there that the Corps of Engineers built the Metallurgical Laboratory in Wah Cantonment in 1976.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam remained associated with the nuclear weapons programme until mid-1974, when he left the country after Ahmadi were declared non-Muslims by the Pakistani Parliament.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] His own relations with Prime minister Bhutto fell out and turned into open hostility after the Ahmadiyya Community was declared as not-Islamic; he lodged a public and powerful protest against Bhutto regarding this issue and gave great criticism to Bhutto over his control over science.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In spite of this, Salam maintained close relations with the theoretical physics division at PAEC who kept him informed about the status of the calculations needed to calculate the performance of the atomic bomb, according to Norman Dombey.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In the 1980s, Salam personally approved many appointments and a large influx of Pakistani scientists to the associateship program at ICTP and CERN, and engaged in research in theoretical physics with his students at the ICTP.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1964, Salam founded the International Centre for Theoretical Physics (ICTP), Trieste, in Italy and served as its director until 1993.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1974, he founded the International Nathiagali Summer College (INSC) to promote science in Pakistan.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] The INSC is an annual meeting of scientists from all over the world who come to Pakistan and hold discussions on physics and science.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Even today, the INSC holds annual meetings, and Salam's pupil Riazuddin has been its director since its start.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1997, the scientists at ICTP commemorated Salam and renamed ICTP as the "Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics".
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Throughout the years, he served on a number of United Nations committees concerning science and technology in developing countries.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam also founded the Third World Academy of Sciences (TWAS) and was a leading figure in the creation of a number of international centres dedicated to the advancement of science and technology.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1979, Salam said: *Physicists believed there are four fundamental forces of nature; the gravitational force, the weak and strong nuclear force, and the electromagnetic force*.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1981, Salam became a founding member of the World Cultural Council.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Although Salam left Pakistan, he did not terminate his connection to home.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] He continued inviting Pakistan's scientists to ICTP, and maintained a research programme for them.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Abdus Salam was a very private individual, who kept his public and personal lives quite separate.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] He married twice; first time to a cousin, the second time as well in accordance with Islamic law.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] At his death, he was survived by three daughters and a son by his first wife, and a son and daughter by his second, Professor Dame Louise Johnson, formerly Professor of molecular biophysics at Oxford University.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Two of his daughters are Anisa Bushra Salam Bajwa and Aziza Rahman.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] Salam was an Ahmadi Muslim, who saw his religion as a fundamental part of his scientific work.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In 1974, the Pakistan parliament made the Second Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan that declared Ahmadis to be non-Muslim.
[src:asia/abdus-salam] In protest, Salam left Pakistan for London.
